{"title_page": "RebbeSoul", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = RebbeSoul\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = RebbeSoul.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = yes\n| alt              = \n| caption          = RebbeSoul at House of Blues, West Hollywood, California\n| background       = solo_singer\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Bruce Burger\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1957|07|11}}\n| birth_place      = [[Utica, New York]], United States\n| origin           = [[Zikhron Ya'akov]], Israel\n| death_date       = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            = [[Jewish rock]], [[folk music|folk]], [[soul music|soul]], [[jazz]], [[worldbeat]]\n| occupation       = Recording artist, producer, singer, songwriter, guitarist, composer, arranger\n| instrument       = Vocals, guitar, [[balalaika]], [[mandolin]], [[bouzouki]], [[Ba\u011flama|saz]]\n| years_active     = 1980-present\n| label            = Global Pacific, [[33rd Street Records|33rd Street]]\n| associated_acts  = Jazzburger, Common Tongue, [[Hamakor (band)|Hamakor]], Shlomit & RebbeSoul, Shlomit Levi\n| website          = {{URL|rebbesoul.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Bruce Burger''' (born July 11, 1957, [[Utica, New York]]), known by his [[stage name]] '''RebbeSoul''', is an American-Israeli Jewish singer, songwriter, multi-instrumentalist, composer, and producer. Performing since the early 1990s, he has released five solo albums and has recorded with the bands [[Hamakor (band)|Hamakor]] and Common Tongue. He has also collaborated with singer [[Shlomit Levi]] of [[Orphaned Land]] for the [[world music]] duo Shlomit & RebbeSoul.\n\n==Early life==\nBurger was born in [[Utica, New York]] to a minimally observant [[Conservative Judaism|Conservative Jewish]] family.<ref name=\"tribune\">{{cite web|author1=Achy Obejas|title=Rebbesoul's art reflects his spiritual awakening|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2004-08-01/news/0408010365_1_jewish-melodies-observe-carlebach|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=Aug 1, 2004}}</ref><ref name=billboard>{{cite news|author1=Trudi Miller Rosenblum|title=RebbeSoul: Choice Hits For Chosen People|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ag4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14&dq=rebbesoul+bruce+burger&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSvc_u7pHKAhVY2GMKHTCYBNMQuwUIJzAA#v=onepage&q=rebbesoul%20bruce%20burger&f=false|accessdate=5 January 2016|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=Sep 30, 1995}}</ref> When he was 12, his parents bought him a plastic guitar, not believing he would take the instrument seriously. He later began playing at local bars, despite being underage.<ref name=\"ynet\">{{cite web|author1=Liron Nagler-Cohen|title=\u05de\u05ea\u05e4\u05dc\u05dc \u05e2\u05dd \u05d4\u05d2\u05d9\u05d8\u05e8\u05d4|url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4077083,00.html|publisher=[[Ynet]]|language=Hebrew|date=June 2, 2011}}</ref> He attended [[Syracuse University]] and graduated with a degree in engineering.\n\n==Career==\nBurger left upstate New York at 22 and moved to [[Los Angeles]], where he worked as a [[session musician]] for various artists, including [[Barbara Mandrell]], and provided music for shows like ''[[Baywatch]]'' and ''[[Cristal (telenovela)|Cristal]]''.<ref name=\"tribune\" /> During this time, he founded a [[jazz fusion]] group called Jazzburger including saxophonist [[Dave Koz]], drummer [[Alex Acu\u00f1a]], and saxophonist [[Cornelius Bumpus]].<ref name=billboard />\n\n===''RebbeSoul'', ''Fringe of Blue'', and ''RebbeSoul-O'' (1993-1999)===\nIn 1992, Burger was invited to a [[Shabbat]] dinner at the home of [[Chabad]] Rabbi Shlomo Schwartz. Moved by the traditional prayers and melodies, Burger felt he had \"found [his] sound\" and decided to start a career in [[Jewish music]].<ref name=\"billboard\" /><ref name=\"ynet\" /> The following year, assembling a band of non-Jewish musicians he knew from his session work, he released his debut album, the self-titled ''RebbeSoul''. One of the album's songs, an instrumental version of [[Avinu Malkeinu]] simply called \"Avinu\", received radio play on the local station [[KOSF|KKSF]].<ref name=\"j\">{{cite web|author1=Suzanne Weiss|title=RebbeSoul leader goes solo|url=http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/5411/rebbesoul-leader-goes-solo/|publisher=[[j. (newspaper)|Jweekly]]|date=April 4, 1997}}</ref>\n\n''RebbeSoul'' attracted the attention of [[Sonoma, California|Sonoma]]-based jazz label Global Pacific, which released Burger's 1995 follow-up, ''Fringe of Blue''. The album's [[electric guitar|electric]] version of \"Avinu\" received praise from ''[[Playboy Magazine]]'' and ''[[The Jewish Week]]'', while the acoustic version was played on [[KTWV]] by host Talaya Trigueros, and the songs \"A Narrow Bridge\" and \"[[Tum Balalaika]]\" appeared on the Illinois college station [[WNIJ]].<ref name=\"billboard\" /><ref name=\"AMG bio\">{{Allmusic | class=artist | id=mn0000870022 | tab=biography | label=RebbeSoul | first= L.| last=Katz | accessdate= 2 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Burger collaborated with playwright Richard Krevolin on ''RebbeSoul-O: A One-Man Musical Journey'', an 85-minute [[one-person show|one-man]] theater piece based on Burger's musical and spiritual journey. Sponsored by the [[American Jewish Committee]], the show premiered in March at the Ovations Theatre in Los Angeles. The soundtrack was composed and performed by Burger, who released it in album form later that year.<ref name=\"j\" /><ref name=\"AMG bio\" />\n\n===Common Tongue and ''Change the World with a Sound'' (1999-2007)===\n\nBurger formed the [[world music]] band Common Tongue in 1999 with percussionist Cassio Duarte, keyboardist Steve Carter, drummer Joel Alpers, bassist Dennis \"Deep Den\" Smith, and singer Neeyah  Lynn Rose. They released their debut album, ''Step Into My World'', in 2000.<ref>{{Allmusic | class=artist | id=mn0000113709 | tab=biography | label=Common Tongue | first= L.| last=Katz | accessdate= 2 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis fourth studio album, ''Change the World with a Sound'', was released in 2002. Duarte, Carter, and Rose were featured on the album, as were rapper Prophet X and singer [[Neshama Carlebach]]. The album reached No. 1 on the [[CMJ]] world music charts was played on over 130 college radio stations.<ref name=\"tribune\" />\n\n===Work in Israel (2007-present)===\nBurger made ''[[aliyah]]'' to [[Israel]] in 2007, settling in the town of [[Zikhron Ya'akov]].<ref name=\"jpost\">{{cite web|author1=Maurice Picow|title=A 'rebbe' with soul|url=http://www.rebbesoul.com/press.html|publisher=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|accessdate=5 February 2016|date=May 3, 2012}} Archived at rebbesoul.com.</ref> There, he produced, arranged, and recorded ''From Another World'' (2010), an album of [[instrumental music|instrumental]] renditions of [[Shlomo Carlebach (musician)|Shlomo Carlebach]] songs. The album received play on the Israeli stations [[Army Radio]] and 88FM.<ref name=\"jpost\" />\n\nIn mid-2010, Burger was introduced to [[Shlomit Levi]], a [[Yemenite Jews in Israel|Yemenite]] singer who had performed with the Israeli metal band [[Orphaned Land]]. They subsequently began performing together as Shlomit & RebbeSoul, and released their debut album, ''The Seal of Solomon'', in 2015.<ref name=\"jpost\" /><ref name=\"jstandard\">{{cite web|author1=Larry Yudelson|title=Connecting through music|url=http://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/connecting-through-music/|publisher=[[The Jewish Standard]]|accessdate=6 February 2016|date=April 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nLater in the year, he produced a series of songs for [[Arab Christians|Christian Arab]] [[oud]] player George Simaan, including a version of \"[[Erev Shel Shoshanim]]\", with Levi and [[Yuval Banay]] of [[Mashina]] contributing Hebrew vocals.<ref name=\"jstandard\" />\n\n==Musical style==\nBurger is known for his diverse sound, drawing from a variety of styles and cultures. Over the course of his career, he has gradually expanded from a conventional [[Jewish rock music|Jewish rock]] sound to incorporate [[folk music|folk]], [[soul music|soul]], [[jazz]], [[new-age music|new-age]] and [[worldbeat]],<ref name=\"ynet\" /><ref>{{Allmusic | class=album | id=mw0000645846 | tab= | label=Fringe of Blue | first=L. | last=Katz | accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Roth, Paula|title=The source of h\u00e4MAKOR -- it's all in the family|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/music/article/the_source_of_haumlmakor_its_all_in_the_family_20080625|website=[[Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|accessdate=6 December 2015|date=Jun 26, 2008}}</ref> as well as sounds from [[South America]]n, [[list of Caribbean music genres|Caribbean]], [[music of West Africa|West African]], [[Middle Eastern music|Middle Eastern]], [[music of Yemen|Yemenite]], and [[Sephardic music]].<ref name=\"billboard\" /><ref>{{Allmusic | class=album | id=mw0000332764 | tab= | label=Rebbe | first=L. | last=Katz | accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Andrew Muchin|title=Sephardic Music Comes Out of the Shadows|url=http://forward.com/articles/9414/sephardic-music-comes-out-of-the-shadows/|publisher=[[The Forward]]|date=March 7, 2003}}</ref> Although primarily a [[guitar]]ist, he also uses a wide variety of instruments in his music, most notably the [[balalaika]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Ben Bresky|title=What is a Balalaika, and what does it sound like?|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/Radio/News.aspx/2812#.Vrlw-NBy3IU|publisher=[[Arutz Sheva]]|format=audio interview|date=Jan 16, 2011}}</ref> Burger attributes his eclectic sound to his years as a session musician, where he was forced to be a \"chameleon\" and play in many different styles.<ref name=\"tribune\" />\n\nWhile Burger occasionally sings on his albums, he places greater emphasis on his instrumental work, saying, \"I am a player that sings, not a singer that plays\".<ref name=\"ynet\" />\n\n==Discography==\n\n===As primary artist===\n*''RebbeSoul'' (1993)\n*''Fringe of Blue'' (1995)\n*''RebbeSoul-O'' (1997)\n*''Change the World with a Sound'' (2002)\n*''Nigun: Voice of the Soul'' (with [[Sam Glaser]]) (2007)\n*''From Another World'' (2010)\n\n;With Common Tongue\n*''Step Into My World'' (2000)\n\n;With [[Hamakor (band)|Hamakor]]\n*''World On Its Side'' (2010)\n\n;With Shlomit & RebbeSoul]\n*''The Seal of Solomon'' (2015)\n\n===Compilation appearances===\n*''Tranceworld: The Inspiration'' (1996, Global Pacific) (\"Prelude\"/\"My Soul Thirsts For You\")\n*''Festival of Lights, Vol. 1'' (1996, [[PolyGram]]) (\"Avinu\")\n*''New Visons: World Rhythms'' (1998, [[Rhino Entertainment|Rhino]]) (\"Call to Freedom\")\n*''Prayer: A Multicultural Journey of Spirit'' (1998, Soundings of the Planet) (\"Prayer for Peace (Harachaman)\")\n*''Spirit of the Heart'' (2003, Rhino) (\"Prelude\"/\"My Soul Thirsts For You\")\n*''[[When Do We Eat? (2005 film)|When Do We Eat?]] Soundtrack'' (2006, JMG) (\"Avinu Malkeinu\")\n*''Celebrate Shabbat'' (2007, [[Craig Taubman|Craig 'N' Co.]]) (\"Bim Bam\")\n*[[Pioneers for a Cure]], ''The Postcard Project'' (2009) (\"Shir Shomer\" with Lynn Rose)\n\n===Other work===\n*[[Walter Ostanek]], ''Putting It Together Vols. 1-2'' (1996) \u2013 [[piano]], [[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n*Various, ''Festival of Lights, Vol 1'' (1996) \u2013 [[record producer|producer]], [[arrangement|arranger]]\n*Linda Hirschhorn, ''Becoming'' (2007) \u2013 [[balalaika]]\n*Rahel, ''Hinay Ma Tov'' (2009) \u2013 featured artist (\"Hinay Ma Tov\", \"Oseh Shalom\", \"Am Yisrael Chai\")\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.rebbesoul.com Official website]\n\n{{Contemporary Jewish religious music}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Utica, New York]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:American world music groups]]\n[[Category:Jewish rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish folk rock groups]]\n[[Category:Balalaika players]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:American multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Jewish jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Hamakor (band) members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = RebbeSoul\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = RebbeSoul.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = yes\n| alt              = \n| caption          = RebbeSoul at House of Blues, West Hollywood, California\n| background       = solo_singer\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Bruce Burger\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1957|07|11}}\n| birth_place      = [[Utica, New York]], United States\n| origin           = [[Zikhron Ya'akov]], Israel\n| death_date       = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            = [[Jewish rock]], [[folk music|folk]], [[soul music|soul]], [[jazz]], [[worldbeat]]\n| occupation       = Recording artist, producer, singer, songwriter, guitarist, composer, arranger\n| instrument       = Vocals, guitar, [[balalaika]], [[mandolin]], [[bouzouki]], [[Ba\u011flama|saz]]\n| years_active     = 1980-present\n| label            = Global Pacific, [[33rd Street Records|33rd Street]]\n| associated_acts  = Jazzburger, Common Tongue, [[Hamakor (band)|Hamakor]], Shlomit & RebbeSoul, Shlomit Levi\n| website          = {{URL|rebbesoul.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Bruce Burger''' (born July 11, 1957, [[Utica, New York]]), known by his [[stage name]] '''RebbeSoul''', is an American-Israeli Jewish singer, songwriter, multi-instrumentalist, composer, and producer. Performing since the early 1990s, he has released five solo albums and has recorded with the bands [[Hamakor (band)|Hamakor]] and Common Tongue. He has also collaborated with singer, [[Shlomit Levi]] of [[Orphaned Land]] for the [[world music]] duo Shlomit & RebbeSoul.\n\n==Early life==\nBurger was born in [[Utica, New York]] to a minimally observant [[Conservative Judaism|Conservative Jewish]] family.<ref name=\"tribune\">{{cite web|author1=Achy Obejas|title=Rebbesoul's art reflects his spiritual awakening|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2004-08-01/news/0408010365_1_jewish-melodies-observe-carlebach|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=Aug 1, 2004}}</ref><ref name=billboard>{{cite news|author1=Trudi Miller Rosenblum|title=RebbeSoul: Choice Hits For Chosen People|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ag4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14&dq=rebbesoul+bruce+burger&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSvc_u7pHKAhVY2GMKHTCYBNMQuwUIJzAA#v=onepage&q=rebbesoul%20bruce%20burger&f=false|accessdate=5 January 2016|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=Sep 30, 1995}}</ref> When he was 12, his parents bought him a plastic guitar, not believing he would take the instrument seriously. He later began playing at local bars, despite being underage.<ref name=\"ynet\">{{cite web|author1=Liron Nagler-Cohen|title=\u05de\u05ea\u05e4\u05dc\u05dc \u05e2\u05dd \u05d4\u05d2\u05d9\u05d8\u05e8\u05d4|url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4077083,00.html|publisher=[[Ynet]]|language=Hebrew|date=June 2, 2011}}</ref> He attended [[Syracuse University]] and graduated with a degree in engineering.\n\n==Career==\nBurger left upstate New York at 22 and moved to [[Los Angeles]], where he worked as a [[session musician]] for various artists, including [[Barbara Mandrell]], and provided music for shows like ''[[Baywatch]]'' and ''[[Cristal (telenovela)|Cristal]]''.<ref name=\"tribune\" /> During this time, he founded a [[jazz fusion]] group called Jazzburger including saxophonist [[Dave Koz]], drummer [[Alex Acu\u00f1a]], and saxophonist [[Cornelius Bumpus]].<ref name=billboard />\n\n===''RebbeSoul'', ''Fringe of Blue'', and ''RebbeSoul-O'' (1993-1999)===\nIn 1992, Burger was invited to a [[Shabbat]] dinner at the home of [[Chabad]] Rabbi Shlomo Schwartz. Moved by the traditional prayers and melodies, Burger felt he had \"found [his] sound\" and decided to start a career in [[Jewish music]].<ref name=\"billboard\" /><ref name=\"ynet\" /> The following year, assembling a band of non-Jewish musicians he knew from his session work, he released his debut album, the self-titled ''RebbeSoul''. One of the album's songs, an instrumental version of [[Avinu Malkeinu]] simply called \"Avinu\", received radio play on the local station [[KOSF|KKSF]].<ref name=\"j\">{{cite web|author1=Suzanne Weiss|title=RebbeSoul leader goes solo|url=http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/5411/rebbesoul-leader-goes-solo/|publisher=[[j. (newspaper)|Jweekly]]|date=April 4, 1997}}</ref>\n\n''RebbeSoul'' attracted the attention of [[Sonoma, California|Sonoma]]-based jazz label Global Pacific, which released Burger's 1995 follow-up, ''Fringe of Blue''. The album's [[electric guitar|electric]] version of \"Avinu\" received praise from ''[[Playboy Magazine]]'' and ''[[The Jewish Week]]'', while the acoustic version was played on [[KTWV]] by host Talaya Trigueros, and the songs \"A Narrow Bridge\" and \"[[Tum Balalaika]]\" appeared on the Illinois college station [[WNIJ]].<ref name=\"billboard\" /><ref name=\"AMG bio\">{{Allmusic | class=artist | id=mn0000870022 | tab=biography | label=RebbeSoul | first= L.| last=Katz | accessdate= 2 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Burger collaborated with playwright Richard Krevolin on ''RebbeSoul-O: A One-Man Musical Journey'', an 85-minute [[one-person show|one-man]] theater piece based on Burger's musical and spiritual journey. Sponsored by the [[American Jewish Committee]], the show premiered in March at the Ovations Theatre in Los Angeles. The soundtrack was composed and performed by Burger, who released it in album form later that year.<ref name=\"j\" /><ref name=\"AMG bio\" />\n\n===Common Tongue and ''Change the World with a Sound'' (1999-2007)===\n\nBurger formed the [[world music]] band Common Tongue in 1999 with percussionist Cassio Duarte, keyboardist Steve Carter, drummer Joel Alpers, bassist Dennis \"Deep Den\" Smith, and singer Neeyah  Lynn Rose. They released their debut album, ''Step Into My World'', in 2000.<ref>{{Allmusic | class=artist | id=mn0000113709 | tab=biography | label=Common Tongue | first= L.| last=Katz | accessdate= 2 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis fourth studio album, ''Change the World with a Sound'', was released in 2002. Duarte, Carter, and Rose were featured on the album, as were rapper Prophet X and singer [[Neshama Carlebach]]. The album reached No. 1 on the [[CMJ]] world music charts was played on over 130 college radio stations.<ref name=\"tribune\" />\n\n===Work in Israel (2007-present)===\nBurger made ''[[aliyah]]'' to [[Israel]] in 2007, settling in the town of [[Zikhron Ya'akov]].<ref name=\"jpost\">{{cite web|author1=Maurice Picow|title=A 'rebbe' with soul|url=http://www.rebbesoul.com/press.html|publisher=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|accessdate=5 February 2016|date=May 3, 2012}} Archived at rebbesoul.com.</ref> There, he produced, arranged, and recorded ''From Another World'' (2010), an album of [[instrumental music|instrumental]] renditions of [[Shlomo Carlebach (musician)|Shlomo Carlebach]] songs. The album received play on the Israeli stations [[Army Radio]] and 88FM.<ref name=\"jpost\" />\n\nIn mid-2010, Burger was introduced to [[Shlomit Levi]], a [[Yemenite Jews in Israel|Yemenite]] singer who had performed with the Israeli metal band [[Orphaned Land]]. They subsequently began performing together as Shlomit & RebbeSoul, and released their debut album, ''The Seal of Solomon'', in 2015.<ref name=\"jpost\" /><ref name=\"jstandard\">{{cite web|author1=Larry Yudelson|title=Connecting through music|url=http://jewishstandard.timesofisrael.com/connecting-through-music/|publisher=[[The Jewish Standard]]|accessdate=6 February 2016|date=April 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nLater in the year, he produced a series of songs for [[Arab Christians|Christian Arab]] [[oud]] player George Simaan, including a version of \"[[Erev Shel Shoshanim]]\", with Levi and [[Yuval Banay]] of [[Mashina]] contributing Hebrew vocals.<ref name=\"jstandard\" />\n\n==Musical style==\nBurger is known for his diverse sound, drawing from a variety of styles and cultures. Over the course of his career, he has gradually expanded from a conventional [[Jewish rock music|Jewish rock]] sound to incorporate [[folk music|folk]], [[soul music|soul]], [[jazz]], [[new-age music|new-age]] and [[worldbeat]],<ref name=\"ynet\" /><ref>{{Allmusic | class=album | id=mw0000645846 | tab= | label=Fringe of Blue | first=L. | last=Katz | accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Roth, Paula|title=The source of h\u00e4MAKOR -- it's all in the family|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/music/article/the_source_of_haumlmakor_its_all_in_the_family_20080625|website=[[Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|accessdate=6 December 2015|date=Jun 26, 2008}}</ref> as well as sounds from [[South America]]n, [[list of Caribbean music genres|Caribbean]], [[music of West Africa|West African]], [[Middle Eastern music|Middle Eastern]], [[music of Yemen|Yemenite]], and [[Sephardic music]].<ref name=\"billboard\" /><ref>{{Allmusic | class=album | id=mw0000332764 | tab= | label=Rebbe | first=L. | last=Katz | accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Andrew Muchin|title=Sephardic Music Comes Out of the Shadows|url=http://forward.com/articles/9414/sephardic-music-comes-out-of-the-shadows/|publisher=[[The Forward]]|date=March 7, 2003}}</ref> Although primarily a [[guitar]]ist, he also uses a wide variety of instruments in his music, most notably the [[balalaika]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Ben Bresky|title=What is a Balalaika, and what does it sound like?|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/Radio/News.aspx/2812#.Vrlw-NBy3IU|publisher=[[Arutz Sheva]]|format=audio interview|date=Jan 16, 2011}}</ref> Burger attributes his eclectic sound to his years as a session musician, where he was forced to be a \"chameleon\" and play in many different styles.<ref name=\"tribune\" />\n\nWhile Burger occasionally sings on his albums, he places greater emphasis on his instrumental work, saying, \"I am a player that sings, not a singer that plays\".<ref name=\"ynet\" />\n\n==Discography==\n\n===As primary artist===\n*''RebbeSoul'' (1993)\n*''Fringe of Blue'' (1995)\n*''RebbeSoul-O'' (1997)\n*''Change the World with a Sound'' (2002)\n*''Nigun: Voice of the Soul'' (with [[Sam Glaser]]) (2007)\n*''From Another World'' (2010)\n\n;With Common Tongue\n*''Step Into My World'' (2000)\n\n;With [[Hamakor (band)|Hamakor]]\n*''World On Its Side'' (2010)\n\n;With Shlomit & RebbeSoul]\n*''The Seal of Solomon'' (2015)\n\n===Compilation appearances===\n*''Tranceworld: The Inspiration'' (1996, Global Pacific) (\"Prelude\"/\"My Soul Thirsts For You\")\n*''Festival of Lights, Vol. 1'' (1996, [[PolyGram]]) (\"Avinu\")\n*''New Visons: World Rhythms'' (1998, [[Rhino Entertainment|Rhino]]) (\"Call to Freedom\")\n*''Prayer: A Multicultural Journey of Spirit'' (1998, Soundings of the Planet) (\"Prayer for Peace (Harachaman)\")\n*''Spirit of the Heart'' (2003, Rhino) (\"Prelude\"/\"My Soul Thirsts For You\")\n*''[[When Do We Eat? (2005 film)|When Do We Eat?]] Soundtrack'' (2006, JMG) (\"Avinu Malkeinu\")\n*''Celebrate Shabbat'' (2007, [[Craig Taubman|Craig 'N' Co.]]) (\"Bim Bam\")\n*[[Pioneers for a Cure]], ''The Postcard Project'' (2009) (\"Shir Shomer\" with Lynn Rose)\n\n===Other work===\n*[[Walter Ostanek]], ''Putting It Together Vols. 1-2'' (1996) \u2013 [[piano]], [[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n*Various, ''Festival of Lights, Vol 1'' (1996) \u2013 [[record producer|producer]], [[arrangement|arranger]]\n*Linda Hirschhorn, ''Becoming'' (2007) \u2013 [[balalaika]]\n*Rahel, ''Hinay Ma Tov'' (2009) \u2013 featured artist (\"Hinay Ma Tov\", \"Oseh Shalom\", \"Am Yisrael Chai\")\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n