{"title_page": "Bernard Hinault", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n|name        = Bernard Hinault\n|image       = Bernard Hinault - Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 2012 - Prologue (2).jpg\n|caption     = Hinault at the [[2012 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9]]\n|alt = Color photograph of Hinault, looking to the left, wearing glasses\n|fullname    = Bernard Hinault\n|nickname    = {{unbulleted list\n|''Le Blaireau'' (The Badger)\n|''Le Patron'' (The Boss)\n}}\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1954|11|14|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Yffiniac]], France\n|height      = {{height|m=1.74}}\n|weight      = {{convert|62|kg|lb stlb|0|abbr=on}}\n|currentteam = Retired\n|discipline  = Road\n|role        = Rider\n| ridertype  = [[Glossary of cycling#all-rounder|All-rounder]]\n|proyears1   = 1975\u20131977\n|proteam1    = [[Gitane\u2013Campagnolo]]\n|proyears2   = 1978\u20131983\n|proteam2    = {{ct|REN|1978}}\n|proyears3   = 1984\u20131986\n|proteam3    = {{ct|LVC|1984}}\n|majorwins   = '''[[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tours]]'''\n:'''[[Tour de France]]'''\n::'''[[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]]''' ([[1978 Tour de France|1978]], [[1979 Tour de France|1979]], [[1981 Tour de France|1981]], [[1982 Tour de France|1982]], [[1985 Tour de France|1985]])\n::[[Points classification in the Tour de France|Points classification]] ([[1979 Tour de France|1979]])\n::[[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|Mountains classification]] ([[1986 Tour de France|1986]])\n::[[Combativity award in the Tour de France|Combativity classification]] ([[1981 Tour de France|1981]], [[1984 Tour de France|1984]], [[1986 Tour de France|1986]])\n::[[Combination classification in the Tour de France|Combination classification]] ([[1981 Tour de France|1981]], [[1982 Tour de France|1982]])\n::28 individual stages (1978\u20131986)\n:'''[[Giro d'Italia]]'''\n::'''[[General classification in the Giro d'Italia|General classification]]''' ([[1980 Giro d'Italia|1980]], [[1982 Giro d'Italia|1982]], [[1985 Giro d'Italia|1985]])\n::7 individual stages (1980, 1982, 1985)\n:'''[[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]'''\n::'''[[General classification in the Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|General classification]]''' ([[1978 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|1978]], [[1983 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|1983]])\n::7 individual stages ([[1978 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|1978]], [[1983 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|1983]])\n'''[[Race stage|Stage races]]'''\n:[[Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]] ([[1977 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|1977]], [[1979 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|1979]], [[1981 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|1981]])\n:[[Tour de Romandie]] ([[1980 Tour de Romandie|1980]])\n'''[[Classic cycle races|One-day races and Classics]]'''\n:[[UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|World Road Race Championships]] (1980)\n:{{nowrap|[[French National Road Race Championships|National Road Race Championships]] (1978)}}\n:[[Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]] ([[1977 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge|1977]], [[1980 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge|1980]])\n:[[Giro di Lombardia]] (1979, 1984)\n:[[Paris\u2013Roubaix]] (1981)\n:[[La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]] (1979, 1983)\n:[[Gent\u2013Wevelgem]] (1977)\n:[[Amstel Gold Race]] (1981)\n:{{nowrap|[[Grand Prix des Nations]] (1977, 1978, 1979, 1982, 1984)}}\n\n'''Other'''\n:[[Super Prestige Pernod International]] (1979\u20131982)\n|medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|{{FRA}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[road bicycle racing]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|World Championships}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1980 UCI Road World Championships|1980 Sallanches]]|Road race}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1981 UCI Road World Championships|1981 Prague]]|Road race}}\n| show-medals = yes\n}}\n\n'''Bernard Hinault''' ({{IPA-fr|b\u025b\u0281.na\u0281 i.no|pron}}; born 14 November 1954) is a French former professional [[cycling|cyclist]]. With 147 professional victories,<ref>{{cite web |title=Bernard Hinault wins |url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/bernard-hinault/statistics/wins |publisher=ProCyclingStats |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> including five in the [[Tour de France]], he is often named among the greatest cyclists of all time.\n\nHinault started cycling as an amateur in his native [[Brittany (administrative region)|Brittany]]. After a successful amateur career, he signed with the [[Gitane\u2013Campagnolo]] team to turn professional in 1975. He took breakthrough victories at both the [[1977 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]] classic and the [[1977 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]] stage race in 1977. In 1978, he won his first two [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tours]]: the [[1978 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]] and the [[1978 Tour de France|Tour de France]]. In the following years, he was the most successful professional cyclist, adding another Tour victory in [[1979 Tour de France|1979]] and a win at the [[1980 Giro d'Italia]]. Although a knee injury forced him to quit the [[1980 Tour de France]] while in the lead, he returned to win the [[1980 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|World Championship road race]] later in the year. He added another Tour victory in [[1981 Tour de France|1981]], before completing his first Giro-Tour double in 1982.\n\nAfter winning the [[1983 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]], a return of his knee problems forced him to miss that year's [[1983 Tour de France|Tour de France]], won by his teammate [[Laurent Fignon]]. Tensions within the [[Renault (cycling team)|Renault team]] led to his leaving and joining [[La Vie Claire]]. With his new team, he raced the [[1984 Tour de France]], being comprehensively beaten by Fignon. He recovered the following year, winning another Giro-Tour double with the help of teammate [[Greg LeMond]]. In the [[1986 Tour de France]], he engaged in an intra-team rivalry with LeMond, who won his first of three Tours. Hinault retired shortly thereafter. {{As of|2019}} he was the most recent French winner of the Tour de France. After his cycling career, Hinault turned to farming, while fulfilling representative duties for the organisers of the Tour de France until 2016.\n\nAll through his career, Hinault was known by the nickname ''le blaireau'' (\"the badger\"); he associated himself with the animal due to its aggressive nature, a trait he embodied on the bike. Within the [[peloton]] (the field of riders), Hinault assumed the role of ''patron'', exercising authority over races he took part in.\n\n==Early life and family==\nHinault was born on 14 November 1954 in the [[Brittany (administrative region)|Breton]] village of [[Yffiniac]], the second oldest of four children to Joseph and Lucie Hinault. The family lived in a cottage named La Cl\u00f4ture, built shortly after Hinault was born. His parents were farmers, and the children often had to help out at harvest time.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=21\u201324}} His father later worked as a [[platelayer]] for the national rail company [[SNCF]].{{sfn|Van Gucht|2015|p=6}} Hinault was described as a \"hyperactive\" child, with his mother nicknaming him \"little [[hooligan]]\".{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=21\u201324}} Hinault was not a good student, but visited the technical college in [[Saint-Brieuc]] for an engineering apprenticeship. He started athletics there, becoming a runner and finishing tenth in the French junior cross-country championship in 1971.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=26\u201327}}\n\nIn December 1974, just before turning professional, Hinault married Martine, who he had met at a family wedding the year before.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=61\u201362}} Their first son, Mickael, was born in 1975,{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=68}} with a second, Alexandre, in 1981.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=150}} Hinault and his family lived in [[Quessoy]], close to Yffiniac, while he was a professional cyclist. After his retirement, they moved to a farm {{convert|64|km|mi|abbr=on}} away in Brittany.<ref name=tourdeforce>{{cite news |last1=Abt |first1=Samuel |authorlink=Samuel Abt | title=Biking's Tour de Force |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/26/magazine/biking-s-tour-de-force.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=8 January 2019 |date=26 June 1983}}</ref> Hinault had bought the {{convert|48|ha|abbr=on}} property near [[Calorguen]] in 1983.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=304}} Martine later served as mayor of Calorguen.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=306}}\n\n==Amateur career==\n{{quote box|quote=\"It seemed natural to him that he had won.\"<br /> Hinault's mother Lucie speaking about his reaction after his first race.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=32}}|width=20%|align=left}}\nHinault came to cycling through his cousin Ren\u00e9, who rode weekend races. At first he had to use the shared family bike, which he rode devotedly. He received his own bike when he was 15 as a reward for passing his school examinations, and used it to travel to college. During the summer of 1971 he made training rides with Ren\u00e9, who had problems keeping up with the sixteen-year old Bernard, even though he was an experienced amateur rider. Hinault received his racing licence from Club Olympique Briochin in late April{{nbsp}}1971 and entered his first race on 2{{nbsp}}May in [[Planguenoual]]. Advised only to try to stay with the other riders, Hinault won the event.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=28\u201331}} Hinault won his first five races, amassing twelve wins from twenty races by the end of the year.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=32}} Also during the summer of 1971, Hinault was at odds with his father about his choice to pursue cycling as a career. Joseph Hinault relented only after his son ran away from home for three days to stay with his cousins, sleeping on straw in the barn.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=34}}\n\nFor 1972, Hinault was allowed to race with the over-18s. At a race in [[Hillion]], he and Ren\u00e9 escaped from the field and reached the finish alone. They crossed the line together to share the victory, to the dismay of the race organisers.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=37\u201338}} The young Hinault was heavily influenced by his trainer at the Club Olympique Briochin, Robert Le Roux, who had earlier worked with [[1965 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|1965 World Champion]] [[Tom Simpson]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=45}} Hinault won nineteen races in his second season as an amateur, including the national junior championship against opposition a year older than him, such as future professional [[Bernard Vallet]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=50\u201351}}{{sfn|Van Gucht|2015|p=11}} He was conscripted into the military at age 18, and did not race throughout 1973. He was unable to join the army's training centre for young athletes and instead served in [[Sissonne]] with the [[21st Marine Infantry Regiment]].{{sfn|Van Gucht|2015|p=11}} Returning to competition overweight, Hinault managed to win his first race of 1974. This was his last season as an amateur and again was highly successful, including a victory in his home town of Yffiniac towards the end of the year, where an alliance formed by four other riders was unable to hold him back. He also competed in [[track cycling]], winning the national [[Individual pursuit|pursuit]] championship.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=52\u201354}} On the road, he took part in the [[\u00c9toile des Espoirs]], a race open to amateurs and young professionals. Hinault finished fifth overall, and second on the time trial stage behind [[UCI Track Cycling World Championships \u2013 Men's individual pursuit|reigning pursuit world champion]] [[Roy Schuiten]]. Towards the end of the season, Hinault turned down an offer to race with the prestigious [[Athletic Club de Boulogne-Billancourt]], instead deciding to turn professional in 1975.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=55\u201356}}\n\n== Professional career ==\n\n=== 1975\u20131977: Gitane ===\nIn January 1975, Hinault turned professional with the [[Gitane\u2013Campagnolo]] team, run by [[UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|former World Champion]] [[Jean Stablinski]], on a lean wage of 2,500{{nbsp}}[[French franc|francs]] per month. The decision to turn professional relatively early was in part taken as, had Hinault raced the 1975 season as an amateur, he would have likely been prevented by the French cycling federation from turning professional before the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] to be part of the [[France at the 1976 Summer Olympics|French team there]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=60\u201361}} Early on, he showed no interest in adhering to the unwritten rules of the peloton, whereby younger riders were expected to show respect towards older ones. At a [[Criterium|criterium race]] in August{{nbsp}}1975 he went up against a coalition of senior riders, who had decided to divide the prize money between them. Hinault won all the intermediate cash prizes until five-time [[Tour de France]] winner [[Eddy Merckx]] declared that Hinault was included in the pact.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=58\u201360}} His results in his first season were impressive, with a seventh place [[1975 Paris\u2013Nice|at Paris\u2013Nice]] and a victory at the [[Circuit de la Sarthe (cycling)|Circuit de la Sarthe]], earning him the Promotion Pernod, the prize for the best new professional in France.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=63\u201364}} However, Hinault showed little willingness to learn the basic trades of cycling from Stablinski, often escaping early in the race instead of learning how to ride inside the peloton. Together with Stablinski entering Hinault into too many races, this led to conflicts between them.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=66\u201368}}\n\nFor 1976, Hinault stayed with Gitane, as former professional [[Cyrille Guimard]], who had just retired from cycling, took over the team and became ''[[directeur sportif]]''. Guimard and Hinault got along well, and the latter was kept out of the high-profile races for 1976, instead focussing on a steady improvement in lesser known races such as [[Paris\u2013Camembert]], which he won. That year, Guimard spurred [[Lucien Van Impe]] to his only win in the Tour de France.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=69\u201375}} Hinault's progress was visible, with a second consecutive victory at the Circuit de la Sarthe, a third place at the [[Grand Prix du Midi Libre]] and a win at the Tour de l'Aude, ensuring him the Prestige Pernod, the award for the best French rider of the season.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=76}} In total, Hinault won 15 races in 1976. At the end of the year, he came sixth at the [[1976 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|World Championship Road Race]], being beaten to the line for fifth by Eddy Merckx.{{sfn|Van Gucht|2015|p=18}}\n\nDuring the [[Classic cycle races|spring classics]] season of 1977, Hinault left the [[1977 Tour of Flanders|Tour of Flanders]] before it had even started, not wanting to risk his health in a rain- and cold-affected race on cobbled roads. This drew him a formal warning by Guimard for his conduct. Three weeks later, Hinault won [[1977 Gent\u2013Wevelgem|Gent\u2013Wevelgem]] in a solo effort after an attack {{convert|30|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the finish.{{sfn|Van Gucht|2015|p=22}} Five days later, at [[1977 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]], Hinault followed an attack by favourite [[Andr\u00e9 Dierickx]], and beat him in the two-man sprint to take his first victory in one of cycling's \"[[Cycling monument|monuments]]\".{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=78\u201379}} In accordance with Guimard's plan to build Hinault up slowly, he did not enter the [[1977 Tour de France|Tour de France]]. He did however start the [[1977 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]], seen as the most important preparation event for the Tour. While in the leader's jersey on the penultimate stage to [[Grenoble]], Hinault attacked up the [[Col de Porte]], leading Van Impe and [[Bernard Th\u00e9venet]] by 1:30 minutes when crossing the summit. On the descent, he misjudged a [[hairpin turn|hairpin corner]] and crashed down the mountainside. A tree saved him from falling far down, while his bike was lost. Hinault then climbed back onto the road, took a new bike and without showing any hesitation, continued on. Up the finishing climb in Grenoble, he briefly dismounted, still shocked from the near-death experience and pushed his bike for about {{convert|20|m|yd|abbr=on}}, before remounting and winning the stage eighty seconds ahead of Van Impe. This also secured him the overall victory ahead of eventual Tour winner Th\u00e9venet.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=80\u201381}} \n\nThis incident was mentioned from a semi-pro rider's perspective in the [[Tim Krabb\u00e9]] book De Runner (The Rider) when the main character is about to descend a Col in the [[Mont Aigoual|Tour de Mont Aigoual]]: {{quote|Curves. I'm afraid, and for good reason. Only three weeks ago, during the Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9, the young up-and-coming Hinault flew out of a curve, into a ravine. Gone. At that moment the French TV audience had every reason to assume that he was lying down there with a broken back. Then he climbed up, was given another bike, rode on, won the stage and went on to win the Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9. A star for ever. Hinault had gone into that ravine a rider, but came out a vedette, and the entire operation lasted no longer than fifteen seconds.\"<ref>{{cite book| title= The Rider|first1=Tim |last1=Krabb\u00e9 |page= 47|isbn=9781582342900|publisher=Bloomsbury|location=London}}</ref>}}\n\nAt the end of the season, Hinault won the [[Grand Prix des Nations]], an [[individual time trial]], with a substantial margin of 3:15 minutes ahead of favourite [[Joop Zoetemelk]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=91}}\n\n=== 1978\u20131983: Renault ===\n====1978: Grand Tour breakthrough====\n[[File:Bernard Hinault 1978 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Hinault at the [[1978 Tour de France]]|alt=Black-and-white photo of Hinault in a cycling jersey, smiling and lifting his right arm in the air]]\nAt the beginning of 1978, the Gitane team was taken over by its parent company, the state-owned car manufacturer [[Renault]], becoming {{ct|REN|1978}}.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=105}} Hinault started the season with second place at [[1978 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]]. He then competed in the [[Crit\u00e9rium International|Crit\u00e9rium National de la Route]]. Trailing [[Raymond Martin (cyclist)|Raymond Martin]] by more than two minutes before the final {{convert|22|km|mi|abbr=on}} time trial, he made up his significant deficit and won the event.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=92}}\n\nHinault then competed in his first three-week [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tour]], at the [[1978 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]], then held at the end of April.{{efn|Since 1995, the [[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]] is held in late August\u2013early September.<ref>{{cite web |title=Did the Vuelta's date change hurt the race? |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/did-the-vueltas-date-change-hurt-the-race/ |website=cyclingnews.com |accessdate=5 August 2019 |date=27 February 2008}}</ref>}} He won the opening prologue time trial in [[Gij\u00f3n]], but then let the leadership switch to [[Ferdi Van Den Haute]]. He won stage 11b, a mountain time trial in [[Barcelona]], and regained the race lead the next day, when he won the stage to [[Santa Margarida de Montbui|La Tossa de Montbui]] after an escape with teammate [[Jean-Ren\u00e9 Bernaudeau]]. He ensured his overall victory by winning stage 18 to [[Amurrio]]. On that stage, he bridged over to escapee [[Andr\u00e9s Gandarias]], who had earlier asked for Hinault's permission to attack. Hinault claimed to have been annoyed into attacking by one of Gandarias's teammates and offered to carry him to the finish. However, the Spaniard was unable to follow his wheel, saying: \"This guy has made me suffer like a dog, he's tougher than Eddy Merckx!\"{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=93\u201395}} In all, Hinault won five stages of the Vuelta. A sixth win was prevented on the final day of the Grand Tour, on which a short time trial was raced in the afternoon, held at [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]] in the [[Basque Country (greater region)|Basque Country]]. The stage was marred by protests and obstructions by supporters of the Basque separatist group [[ETA (separatist group)|ETA]]. Hinault himself had sand thrown into his eyes, but won the stage nonetheless, only to find that the results would not count due to the surrounding circumstances.{{sfn|Van Gucht|2015|pages=35\u201341}}\n\nAhead of his first Tour de France, Hinault raced in the [[1978 Tour de Suisse|Tour de Suisse]], where he did not feature prominently. He then travelled to the [[French National Road Race Championships|French Road Race Championship]], held at [[Sarrebourg]]. He launched an escape, on which he rode {{convert|55|km|mi|abbr=on}} solo, leading the rest of his competitors by more than six minutes by the start of the last lap. However, he had forgotten to eat enough and suffered from [[hypoglycemia]] during the last part of the race, crossing the finish line to take the title severely weakened. His victory allowed him to wear the French ''[[Flag of France|tricolore]]'' jersey for the following year.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=97}}\n\n{{quote box|quote=\"He marched forward like [[Napoleon]]. He took all the responsibility, stood in the front line, was spat at by the crowd.\"<br /> Fellow rider [[Paul Sherwen]] describing Hinault's role in the riders' strike at [[Valence-d'Agen]] during the [[1978 Tour de France]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=85 & 90}}|width=20%|align=right}}\nIn the [[1978 Tour de France|Tour de France]], Hinault fell behind early to challenger Zoetemelk when Renault lost two minutes to [[Mercier (cycling team)|Mercier]] during the [[team time trial]]. On stage 8, the first longer individual time trial, Hinault gained back 59 seconds on Zoetemelk, while the previous two Tour winners, Van Impe and Th\u00e9venet, lost so much time that they were now counted out from chances of an overall win.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|p=113}} Hinault rode conservatively in the [[Pyrenees]] to stay within striking distance of Zoetemelk.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=98\u201399}} On stage 12a, from [[Tarbes]] to [[Valence-d'Agen]], he firmly imprinted his authority on the race, although not by riding. The riders had been complaining about split stages, where more than one would be held on one day, as was the case on 12{{nbsp}}July. When they reached the finishing town, they dismounted their bikes and walked to the finish line in protest. Hinault was chosen by his fellow competitors to be the spokesperson of the strike. Journalist Felix Magowan wrote: \"Before today's strike, people were asking if the Tour had a boss. Today that was answered. His name is Hinault.\"{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=85\u201391}} Following the strike, Hinault had trouble sleeping and was caught out the next day, a stage in the [[Massif Central]], forcing his team into a long chase. Thus weakened and slowed by spectator interference at a bike change, he lost 1:40 minutes to Zoetemelk on the following day's uphill time trial.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|p=115}} Hinault countered the next day ''en route'' to [[Saint-\u00c9tienne]] during stage 15, breaking away with [[Hennie Kuiper]]. By the finish, the two had been reeled back, but Hinault contested the finishing sprint, winning the stage. The following day, stage 16 to [[Alpe d'Huez]], ended with Zoetemelk, Hinault and the temporary leader of the [[General classification in the Tour de France|general classification]] and thus yellow jersey wearer [[Michel Pollentier]] separated by only 18 seconds. However, Pollentier was disqualified for trying to cheat his [[doping in sport|doping]] test, leaving Hinault and Zoetemelk to fight out the overall victory. On the final mountain stage, Hinault put his rival under pressure, but was unable to make up any time. He then clinched the yellow jersey in the final time trial, gaining more than four minutes to win his first Tour de France with an advantage of 3:56 minutes.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=100\u2013102}} Following his Tour win, he finished fifth at the [[1978 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|World Championships]], before once more winning the Grand Prix des Nations, this time ahead of [[Francesco Moser]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=103}}\n\n====1979: Second Tour victory and Classics success====\nThe 1979 season started slowly for an off-form Hinault. He bounced back at the [[1979 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne|La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]] classic in April, when he caught up to a breakaway by [[Giuseppe Saronni]] and [[Bernt Johansson]], outsprinting the former to win the race. He then beat Zoetemelk to victory at the [[1979 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]], winning four stages. He won the race by over ten minutes, also taking the [[Points classification|points]] and [[King of the Mountains|mountain classifications]]. In the coming weeks ahead of the Tour, he proved his willingness to assist his teammates to ensure their loyalty, helping [[Lucien Didier]] win the [[Tour de Luxembourg]] and finishing second behind [[Roland Berland]] in the National Championship race.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=117\u2013118}}\n[[File:Joop Zoetemelk, Bestanddeelnr 930-4019.jpg|thumb|[[Joop Zoetemelk]] ''(pictured in 1979)'' was Hinault's strongest competitor during his first [[Tour de France]] victories.|alt=Black-and-white photograph of Zoetemelk, wearing cycling gear]]\nThe [[1979 Tour de France|Tour de France]] was again a two-way battle between Hinault and Zoetemelk. In the prologue, Hinault was fourth, on the same time as the Dutchman. The mountain stages started immediately thereafter, with Hinault winning the mountain time trial on stage 2, taking over the yellow jersey. He also won the next stage into [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]]. The team time trial on stage{{nbsp}}4 again went Zoetemelk's way, as his Mercier team took back 41 seconds on Hinault's Renault squad. Zoetemelk now was only 12 seconds behind Hinault. On stage 8, in another team time trial, Renault fared much better, and Hinault extended his advantage to 1:18 minutes. The next day however, on a stage containing [[Cobblestone#Use in cycling|cobbled sections]], Hinault suffered two [[Flat tire#Bicycles|punctures]], losing almost four minutes and the race lead to Zoetemelk.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|p=119}} He took back 36 seconds on the time trial in [[Brussels]] on stage 11 before regaining the race lead after another time trial, uphill to [[Avoriaz]] on stage 15. At this stage, he led Zoetemelk by 1:48 minutes, with third-placed Kuiper already more than 12 minutes behind. Hinault gained another minute on stage 16, before Zoetemelk regained 47 seconds up Alpe d'Huez three days later. The final time trial of the Tour went Hinault's way once again, extending his advantage by a further 69 seconds. He also took the next stage in a slightly uphill sprint finish.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=119\u2013122}} On the final stage towards the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in [[Paris]], traditionally [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es stage in the Tour de France|a ceremonious affair without attacks]], Zoetemelk and Hinault broke away, with both gapping the field and Hinault taking another stage victory. Zoetemelk finished 3:07 minutes behind Hinault, but then had ten minutes added to his time for failing a doping test. The next finisher, [[Joaquim Agostinho]], was almost half an hour behind the winner.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=114\u2013116}}\n\nTowards the end of the season, Hinault won his second cycling monument, the [[1979 Giro di Lombardia|Giro di Lombardia]]. He had escaped from the field {{convert|150|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the finish, but was later joined by some other riders. Only [[Silvano Contini]] finished with him, with the next group more than three minutes behind. The victory also secured that Hinault won his first of four consecutive [[Super Prestige Pernod International]] competitions, the award handed to the best rider of the season.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=123\u2013124}}\n\n====1980: Attempt at the Triple Crown====\nAs was often the case, Hinault started the season slowly in 1980, withdrawing from [[1980 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=129}} He then entered [[1980 Paris\u2013Roubaix|Paris\u2013Roubaix]], partly to prepare for the cobbled sections in the upcoming Tour de France, and finished fourth.{{sfn|Moore|2014|p=25}} A week later, he scored one of his most memorable wins at [[1980 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]]. As soon as the riders left [[Li\u00e8ge]], snow began to fall, soon turning into a blizzard. Hinault wanted to abandon, as had many others, including all but one of his teammates. He was convinced to carry on until the feeding station at [[Bastogne]], where the snow had turned into rain. Only 21 riders were left by this point. Hinault removed his rain cape and attacked, catching up to the leaders and carried on by himself, winning with a margin of almost ten minutes ahead of Kuiper. The victory came at a price, as his right index and middle fingers took weeks to recover from [[frostbite]], and caused him pain for several years.<ref>{{cite web |title=Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge's cold memories |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/liege-bastogne-lieges-cold-memories/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=16 August 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816165809/http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/liege-bastogne-lieges-cold-memories/ |archivedate=16 August 2018 |date=23 April 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHinault and Guimard then turned their attention to the only Grand Tour he had not won yet: the [[Giro d'Italia]]. They hoped that Hinault would be able to reproduce a feat Eddy Merckx had achieved in 1974, winning the Giro, the Tour and the World Championship in the same year.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=131}} This is commonly referred to as the [[Triple Crown of Cycling]].{{efn|Since Merckx, only [[Stephen Roche]] managed to repeat the Triple Crown, in 1987.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Cossins |first1=Peter |title=Crowning achievement: How Stephen Roche completed his shock Triple Crown |url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/crowning-achievement-stephen-roche-completed-shock-triple-crown-352929 |magazine=[[Cycling Weekly]] |accessdate=16 August 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816170637/https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/crowning-achievement-stephen-roche-completed-shock-triple-crown-352929 |archivedate=16 August 2018 |date=30 September 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}\n\nHinault started the [[1980 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]] as odds-on favourite, pitted against local riders Francesco Moser and Giuseppe Saronni, who had the home crowd on their side. Following a fourth place at the prologue in [[Genoa]], Hinault made a spontaneous visit to [[Fausto Coppi]]'s home of [[Castellania, Piedmont|Castellania]], paying respect to the first rider ever to have won Giro and Tour in the same year. On stage 5, a time trial to [[Pisa]], Hinault took over the race leader's [[pink jersey]]. He then relinquished his lead to [[Roberto Visentini]], who was not considered to be a contender for the final victory. On stage 14, he attacked when the peloton relaxed after an intermediate sprint, winning the stage ahead of [[Wladimiro Panizza]], who took the race lead. Hinault then made the decisive move of the race on stage 20, when he attacked on the tough climb of the [[Stelvio Pass]]. He caught up with his teammate Bernaudeau, and both carried on for the remaining {{convert|80|km|mi|abbr=on}} of the stage together. Hinault gifted the stage victory to his teammate, while he clinched the overall victory almost six minutes ahead of Panizza.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=131\u2013134}}\n\nIn the [[1980 Tour de France|Tour de France]], Hinault was once again set to duel with Joop Zoetemelk, who had moved to the dominant {{ct|TIR|1980}} squad. Hinault won the prologue in [[Frankfurt]], Germany, five seconds ahead of [[Gerrie Knetemann]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=134}} On stage{{nbsp}}5 from Li\u00e8ge to [[Lille]], which contained cobbled sections used in [[Paris\u2013Roubaix]], conditions were poor with rain and heavy winds. Hinault called for the field to take a slow tempo, but when Zoetemelk's teammate [[Jan Raas]] attacked, he went after him. He eventually found himself in a group with several other riders, while Zoetemelk was distanced. At {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the finish, he followed another attack from Kuiper and won the sprint at the line. The next stage was set to contain more cobbled roads, but on Hinault's protest, most of the worst parts were taken out. Hinault had however suffered damage to his left knee on the stage to Lille.{{sfn|Moore|2014|pages=27\u201331}} Hinault finished only fifth on stage 11's individual time trial, won by Zoetemelk. While he regained the yellow jersey, Zoetemelk was second, only 21 seconds behind.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|pp=125\u2013126}} With his [[tendinitis]] worsening, he carried on until the end of stage 12, just before the race was headed for the first high mountains in the [[Pyrenees]]. That night, Hinault and Guimard told the race organisers, [[Jacques Goddet]] and [[F\u00e9lix L\u00e9vitan]], that he would abandon the race, while still in the lead.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Besan\u00e7on |first1=Lucas |title=1980 : Hinault, Maillot jaune, abandonne en larmes |trans-title=1980: Hinault, yellow jersey, gives up in tears |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/tour-de-france-cycliste/1980-hinault-maillot-jaune-abandonne-en-larmes-09-07-2013-2967383.php |newspaper=[[Le Parisien]] |accessdate=16 August 2018 |date=9 July 2013|language=French}}</ref> He left the race at night, not informing the press, which led to a fallout with the media that took years to recover.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=139\u2013141}}<ref name=\"cn_greatest\">{{cite web |last1=Robinson |first1=Mark |title=Bernard Hinault: The greatest of them all? |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/bernard-hinault-the-greatest-of-them-all/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=16 August 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816175446/http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/bernard-hinault-the-greatest-of-them-all/ |archivedate=16 August 2018 |date=14 November 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In Hinault's absence, Zoetemelk duly won his only Tour de France.{{sfn|Moore|2014|p=31}} Insinuations that Zoetemelk's victory had been a gift through Hinault's absence were countered by Hinault himself: \"My problems were of my own making. It is always the absent rider who is at fault. I was absent and he took my place.\"{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|p=129}}\n\n{{quote box|quote=\"Five laps from the finish it was obvious that no one was going to beat him. That was how he operated. It was just brutal. That was my introduction to the world of Bernard Hinault.\"<br /> [[Philippa York|Robert Millar]]{{efn|Millar later in life had a gender transition and is now known as [[Philippa York]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fotheringham|first1=William|title=Philippa York: 'I've known I was different since I was a five-year-old'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/jul/06/philippa-york-gender-transition-cyclist-robert-millar|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=1 May 2018|date=6 July 2017}}</ref> For the purpose of this article, her name and gender from the 1980s are used.}} describing his experience riding next to Hinault during the [[1980 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|1980 World Championship road race]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=146}}|width=25%|align=right}}\nHinault returned from the disappointment of the Tour to start at the [[1980 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|World Championship road race]], held on a very tough parcours in [[Sallanches]], France, often named the hardest course in the history of the event.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Owen |first1=Tom |title=The Hardest Worlds? Could Innsbruck be the toughest World Championship road race yet? |url=https://www.eurosport.com/cycling/world-championships/2018/cycling-news-the-hardest-worlds-could-innsbruck-be-the-toughest-world-championship-road-race-yet_sto6940250/story.shtml |publisher=[[Eurosport]] |accessdate=8 January 2019 |date=30 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108130647/https://www.eurosport.com/cycling/world-championships/2018/cycling-news-the-hardest-worlds-could-innsbruck-be-the-toughest-world-championship-road-race-yet_sto6940250/story.shtml|archivedate=8 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cossins |first1=Peter |title=The top 10 World road races |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/the-top-10-world-road-races/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=8 January 2019 |date=22 September 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190108130651/http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/the-top-10-world-road-races/|archivedate=8 January 2019}}</ref> Hinault had broken away about {{convert|80|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the finish with several riders. On the last lap, he dropped his last companion, [[Gianbattista Baronchelli]], on the steepest part of a climb and soloed to victory. It had been a race of attrition with only 15 out of 107 riders reaching the finish.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=145\u2013146}}<ref name=\"cn_greatest\"/>\n\n====1981: Winning a third Tour de France====\nHinault had never made his dislike for riding on cobbled roads a secret. The most prominent race of this character, Paris\u2013Roubaix, was met with particular disdain, even though he never finished lower than thirteenth. After the 1980 edition, he had said to organiser Goddet: \"You will never see me in this circus again.\"{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=147}} However, he returned for [[1981 Paris\u2013Roubaix|1981]], saying that he did so out of respect for his stature as World Champion. He suffered seven crashes and tyre punctures, but reached the finish at [[Roubaix Velodrome|the velodrome]] with the lead group, where he outsprinted favourites [[Roger De Vlaeminck]] and Moser.{{sfn|Moore|2014|pages=31\u201332}} One-and-a-half weeks earlier, he had already added a victory at the [[1981 Amstel Gold Race|Amstel Gold Race]].{{sfn|Moore|2011|p=80}} Furthermore, he also won the Crit\u00e9rium International and again dominated the [[1981 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]], winning by twelve minutes ahead of Agostinho.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=179}}\n\nAt the [[1981 Tour de France|Tour de France]], Hinault took an early lead by winning the prologue, then relinquished the yellow jersey to Knetemann and later to [[Phil Anderson (cyclist)|Phil Anderson]]. On the time trial to Pau on stage 7, he regained the lead and never lost the jersey, beating Van Impe by almost a quarter of an hour.{{sfn|Wheatcroft|2013|p=250}} He won five stages, including all four individual time trials.{{sfn|Laget|Laget|Cazaban|Montgermont|2013|p=220}} Amidst media criticism that he was riding too defensively in the mountains, he also took victory in the [[Alps]] on a stage to [[Le Pleynet]].{{sfn|Moore|2011|p=81}}\n\nAt the [[1981 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|World Championship in Prague]], Czechoslovakia, Hinault failed to defend his title. Having bridged a two-and-a-half-minute gap to a strong lead group on his own, he came third in the final sprint, behind [[Freddy Maertens]] and Saronni.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=180}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Victoria de Maertens al \"sprint\" |trans-title=Victory for Maertens in \"sprint\"|url=https://elpais.com/diario/1981/09/01/deportes/368143214_850215.html |accessdate=13 November 2019 |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |agency=[[EFE]] |date=1 September 1981 |location=Prague|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n====1982: Achieving the Giro-Tour double====\n[[File:Bernard Hinault (1982).jpg|thumb|upright|Hinault at the [[1982 Tour de France]]|alt=Black-and-white photograph of Hinault's face, smiling]]\nHinault returned to the Giro in [[1982 Giro d'Italia|1982]]. He looked set for victory after the first two weeks, having taken a significant lead after wins in the stage{{nbsp}}3 time trial and stage 12 to [[Campitello Matese]]. However, on stage 17 to [[Boario Terme]], Guimard and the Renault team misjudged the toughness of the climb and Hinault lost the lead to Silvano Contini. He hit back the next day, winning the stage to [[Montecampione]], turning the race in his favour.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=181\u2013182}}\n\nIn \"his most uneventful Tour\",{{sfn|Wheatcroft|2013|p=251}} Hinault never looked in trouble on his way to completing the Giro-Tour double at the [[1982 Tour de France|Tour de France]]. He won the prologue in [[Basel]], Switzerland, before the lead briefly turned to [[Ludo Peeters]] and Phil Anderson. Hinault regained the yellow jersey after the first time trial and won the overall classification easily. He took four stages, including again the final one on the Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es, this time from a bunch sprint.{{sfn|Wheatcroft|2013|p=251}} His participation in the final-stage sprint was seen as an answer to critics, who had once again lamented that Hinault had ridden the Tour without ''[[panache]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abt |first1=Samuel |authorlink=Samuel Abt |title=Hinault Closes Fast in Capturing Tour |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/07/26/sports/hinault-closes-fast-in-capturing-tour.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=8 January 2019 |date=26 July 1982}}</ref> Zoetemelk was again the runner-up, more than six minutes behind Hinault.{{sfn|Laget|Laget|Cazaban|Montgermont|2013|p=224}} Later in the season, Hinault added another victory at the Grand Prix des Nations.{{sfn|Wheatcroft|2013|p=251}}\n\n====1983: Second Vuelta and the ascent of Fignon====\nSince 1981, Hinault had been joined at Renault by two young talents, [[Laurent Fignon]] and the American [[Greg LeMond]].{{sfn|Moore|2011|p=66}} Both joined Hinault for the [[1983 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]], where he faced stiff competition from local riders like [[Marino Lejarreta]], [[Juli\u00e1n Gorospe]], and [[Alberto Fern\u00e1ndez]]. Six days before the race started, he had won [[1983 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne|La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]] for a second time. On stage{{nbsp}}4 of the Vuelta, Fignon attacked and won, but Lejarreta, the defending champion, had followed him and gained time on Hinault. Hinault came back and took the lead the following day on the mountain stage to [[Castellar de n'Hug]]. However, a day later, the Spanish teams jointly attacked and Lejarreta moved ahead of Hinault, who was 22 seconds down. At the uphill time trial at [[Panticosa|Balneario de Panticosa]], he suffered and finished more than two minutes behind Lejarreta. Hinault joined forces with Kuiper and Saronni to attack on stage 10 to [[Soria]], affected by crosswinds. He was in trouble again on stage 14, affected by returning pain in his knee; at one point he trailed his rivals by more than five minutes, but regained contact. In the time trial around [[Valladolid]] on stage 15b, Hinault won, now just ten seconds behind Gorospe, the new leader in the general classification. The following day brought the last mountain stage and Renault put pressure on Gorospe from early on. Hinault, joined by Lejarreta and [[Vicente Belda]], escaped for {{convert|80|km|mi|abbr=on}}, distancing Gorospe by over twenty minutes with Hinault taking victory in [[\u00c1vila, Spain|\u00c1vila]], sealing his second Vuelta victory.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=186\u2013190}} Due to the tightly fought battle between Hinault and his Spanish competitors, the 1983 race is described on the Vuelta's website as \"one of the most beautiful and spectacular\" editions.<ref>{{cite web |title=A\u00f1o 1983 |trans-title=Year 1983|url=http://historia.lavuelta.com/es/anio.asp?a=1983 |website=LaVuelta.com |publisher=Unipublic |accessdate=16 August 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816204916/http://historia.lavuelta.com/es/anio_info.asp?_=1534452557208&a=1983 |archivedate=16 August 2018 |language=Spanish |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the Vuelta, Hinault's tendinitis returned. After the race, he made two failed attempts to get back into racing, but eventually announced that he would miss the [[1983 Tour de France|Tour de France]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=194}} In his absence, teammate Fignon won the event on his first attempt.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Stars aus dem Schatten |trans-title=Stars from the Shadow|journal=[[Der Spiegel]] |date=25 July 1983 |issue=30/1983 |page=129 |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-14018351.html |language=German|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> Hinault tried another comeback at a post-Tour criterium,{{efn|In the weeks after the [[Tour de France]], [[criterium]] races are held, mostly in France, Belgium, and the Netherlands, in which the competitors of the Tour appear and are allowed to wear the jerseys of the classifications they won during the event. In Hinault's days, these races provided appearance fees essential to the riders, since wages were low. The results of the race are usually agreed upon between the riders and the organisers beforehand.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Better |first1=Michael |title=Post-Tour criteriums keep the spectacle alive a little while longer |url=https://www.velonews.com/2015/07/news/post-tour-criteriums-keep-the-spectacle-alive-a-little-while-longer_379802 |website=[[VeloNews]] |accessdate=9 August 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190809093403/https://www.velonews.com/2015/07/news/post-tour-criteriums-keep-the-spectacle-alive-a-little-while-longer_379802 |archivedate=9 August 2019 |date=27 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} but the pain returned and he did not race for the remainder of the season.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=194\u2013195}}\n\n=== 1984\u20131986: La Vie Claire ===\n====1984: Defeat at Fignon's hands====\nBy 1983, the relationship between Hinault and Guimard had deteriorated to a point where the former described their relationship as \"war\".{{sfn|Moore|2014|p=132}} Hinault forced a choice on the Renault team to either release him or oust Guimard. The team decided to stick with their ''directeur sportif'', leading Hinault to search for a new team. He joined forces with businessman [[Bernard Tapie]] to form the new {{ct|LVC|1984}} squad. Their ''directeur sportif'' became Swiss coach {{interlanguage link|Paul K\u00f6chli|fr}}, who had made a name for himself with innovative and effective training methods, leaving Hinault a lot of freedom while at the same time scientifically measuring his progress.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=220\u2013226}} As part of his connection with Tapie, Hinault also contributed to the development of the [[Bicycle pedal#Clipless pedals|clipless pedal]], created by Look, another company owned by Tapie.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Smythe |first1=Simon |title=Icons of cycling: Look's revolutionary clipless pedals |url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/product-news/look-clipless-pedals-165379 |magazine=[[Cycling Weekly]] |accessdate=9 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109140213/https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/product-news/look-clipless-pedals-165379 |archivedate=9 January 2019 |date=7 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wilcockson |first1=John |title=Inside Cycling with John Wilcockson: LeMond, Hinault and the Tapie connection |url=https://www.velonews.com/2005/11/news/inside-cycling-with-john-wilcockson-lemond-hinault-and-the-tapie-connection_9177 |website=[[VeloNews]] |publisher=Pocket Outdoor Media, LLC. |accessdate=9 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109140218/https://www.velonews.com/2005/11/news/inside-cycling-with-john-wilcockson-lemond-hinault-and-the-tapie-connection_9177 |archivedate=9 January 2019 |date=18 November 2005}}</ref>\n\nHinault returned to racing at the [[Volta a la Comunitat Valenciana]], where he won the final stage. He then took victory at the [[Four Days of Dunkirk]]. But his spring campaign lacked major successes. At the [[1984 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]], he came second to [[Mart\u00edn Ram\u00edrez (cyclist)|Mart\u00edn Ram\u00edrez]], who later claimed that Hinault and his team had tried to intimidate him during the final stage of the race.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=230\u2013231}} A memorable episode occurred during the [[1984 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]], a race he finished third overall. During stage{{nbsp}}5 to [[La Seyne-sur-Mer]], Hinault was descending in a lead group with several other favourites. As they reached the valley, the road was blocked by protesters, unhappy with the announced closure of a dockyard at [[La Ciotat]]. While the other riders stopped, he drove into the group head-on, dismounted, and punched the protester closest to him. In the ensuing fist fight, Hinault suffered a broken rib.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=199\u2013201}}\n\nThe [[1984 Tour de France|Tour de France]] was made out to be the big duel between Hinault and Fignon, who had just won the French National Championship.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=230\u2013231}}{{sfn|Moore|2014|p=133}} Hinault won the prologue, but Renault took the team time trial, 55 seconds ahead of La Vie Claire. He lost another 49 seconds to Fignon in the first long individual time trial, a discipline he had previously dominated. Following the second time trial, Hinault was only seventh on general classification, two minutes behind his adversary. The next stage led to Alpe d'Huez. Hinault attacked on the [[Rampe de Laffrey]], but Fignon was able to respond. The two exchanged attacks on the way up the climb, but it was in the valley that Hinault was able to draw out a gap of about a minute. On Alpe d'Huez itself, he was first passed by eventual stage winner [[Luis Herrera (cyclist)|Luis Herrera]]. When he started to slow, Fignon caught up to him and eventually dropped Hinault, who lost a further three minutes. He ultimately finished the Tour in second place, a significant ten minutes behind Fignon.{{sfn|Moore|2014|pages=133\u2013140}}\n\nHinaut managed to bounce back from his Tour defeat in the fall. In late September, he took his fifth and final victory at the Grand Prix des Nations, riding the {{convert|90|km|mi|abbr=on}} time trial at a then record speed of {{convert|44.19|kph|mph|abbr=on}}. Fignon could only manage fourth, more than two minutes behind. Next, he won the [[Trofeo Baracchi]], a two-man time trial, in which he competed with Moser. He then won the [[1984 Giro di Lombardia|Giro di Lombardia]] for a second time, breaking away from the group of favourites {{convert|10|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the finish.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=251\u2013253}}\n\n====1985: The second Giro-Tour double====\nFor 1985, Greg LeMond switched teams from Renault to join Hinault at La Vie Claire.{{sfn|Moore|2011|p=138}} Together, they entered the [[1985 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]. During the race, Hinault was met with hostility from the home crowd, who supported local rider Francesco Moser. On the stage 12 time trial, Hinault took the pink jersey and opened the decisive gap to Moser, who would eventually finish second. During the stage however, Hinault was spat at by spectators and almost knocked over, even though his team car rode behind him with the door opened the entire time to ensure that bystanders would have a harder time impeding him. Hinault won his third Giro with a margin of just over a minute.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=254\u2013255}}\n\nIn the [[1985 Tour de France|Tour de France]], Fignon did not take part due to an Achilles heel injury. Hinault therefore entered the race as the favourite. He took victory in the prologue in his native [[Brittany (administrative region)|Brittany]]. La Vie Claire won the stage{{nbsp}}3 team time trial by over a minute. The next day, Hinault's teammate [[Kim Andersen (cyclist)|Kim Andersen]] took over the yellow jersey. Hinault supported him over the next days, even going so far as dropping back when Andersen punctured to lead him back into the peloton, showing his loyalty to riders who would later have to assist him. On stage 8, a time trial to [[Strasbourg]], Hinault took back the race lead, winning the stage by more than two minutes ahead of [[Stephen Roche]]. While the race travelled through the Alps and in a second time trial, he consolidated his lead, building an advantage of five-and-a-half minutes on LeMond, who was now second overall.{{sfn|Moore|2011|pages=150\u2013160}}\n\n{{quote box|quote=\"I'll stir things up to help Greg win, and I'll have fun doing it. That's a promise.\"<br /> Hinault pledging his support for [[Greg LeMond]] for the [[1986 Tour de France]] in an interview at the [[1985 Tour de France|1985 race]].{{sfn|Moore|2011|p=160}}|width=20%|align=right}}\nOn stage 14 to Saint-\u00c9tienne, LeMond finished two minutes ahead of a group containing Hinault. Involved in a crash with other riders, Hinault crossed the finish line with a broken nose. Around the same time, he started to experience symptoms of [[bronchitis]]. On stage 17, he showed signs of weakness and was unable to stay with the other leaders on the [[Col du Tourmalet]]. LeMond meanwhile followed an attack by Roche, but was forbidden by the team to cooperate to distance Hinault. LeMond would later claim that the team had deceived him by telling him that Hinault was closer behind than he actually was. Hinault eventually finished the stage just over a minute behind LeMond. The time LeMond waited may have been enough so that the two teammates would have contested the [[Maillot Jaune]] in the penultimate time trial. In the penultimate day's time trial, LeMond won the stage, but only five seconds ahead of Hinault, not enough to surpass him. This secured Hinault a record-equalling fifth Tour victory, by just under two minutes over his younger teammate. After the finish, he publicly pledged that he would support LeMond's bid for a first Tour victory the following year.{{sfn|Moore|2011|pages=150\u2013160}}\n\n====1986: The final season====\n[[File:Hautes-Alpes Col De L'Izoard Tour De France Hinault 071986 - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Hinault climbing the [[Col d'Izoard]] during the [[1986 Tour de France]]. It was here that he lost significant time on rival [[Greg LeMond]], losing the yellow jersey by the end of the stage.|alt=Color photograph of Hinault on his bike, climbing a mountain while wearing a yellow jersey]]\nIn January 1986, Hinault was given the [[Legion of Honour]] by French president [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]]. He had, already in 1982, announced that he would retire from cycling on his 32nd birthday, in November 1986.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=267\u2013268}}\n\nEven though Hinault had pledged support for LeMond for the [[1986 Tour de France|Tour de France]], a lot of public attention was given to the possibility of him winning a record sixth Tour. Their La Vie Claire team was seen as dominant,<ref name=tenstages>{{cite web |last1=Pickering |first1=Edward |title=10 stages that shook the Tour de France |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/10-stages-that-shook-the-tour-de-france/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=14 November 2018 |date=17 July 2017}}</ref> with Laurent Fignon as the most likely challenger.<ref name=alpedhuez>{{cite web |last1=Henrys |first1=Colin |title=Tour de France classics: Bernard Hinault and Greg LeMond on Alpe d'Huez in 1986 |url=https://roadcyclinguk.com/racing/tour-de-france-classics-bernard-hinault-greg-lemond-alpe-dhuez-1986.html |website=Road Cycling UK |accessdate=14 November 2018 |date=7 July 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Moore|2011|p=188}} Hinault finished third in the prologue, two seconds ahead of LeMond and Fignon.{{sfn|Moore|2011|p=167}} In the team time trial on stage 2, Fignon and {{ct|SUG|1986}} gained almost two minutes on La Vie Claire, partly due to Hinault deciding that the squad would wait for two struggling riders, [[Niki R\u00fcttimann]] and [[Guido Winterberg]].{{sfn|Moore|2011|pages=193\u2013195}} Hinault then won the time trial on stage 9, gaining an additional 44 seconds on LeMond, who suffered a broken wheel and had to change his bike. Meanwhile, Fignon fell behind and later abandoned the race.{{sfn|Moore|2011|pages=198\u2013199}} On stage 12, from [[Bayonne]] to Pau, Hinault attacked with [[Pedro Delgado]]. The pair gained more than four-and-a-half minutes on LeMond, with Delgado taking the stage win. Hinault was now in the lead of the general classification, 5:25 minutes ahead of LeMond.{{sfn|Moore|2011|pages=209\u2013211}} Even though his lead was significant, he attacked again the following day, on the descent of the Col du Tourmalet, the first climb of the day. By the top of the next climb, the [[Col d'Aspin]], he led the rest of the field by two minutes. However, joint effort behind brought him back before the final ascent up to the ski station of [[Superbagn\u00e8res]]. Hinault then cracked, coming in ninth, 4:39 minutes behind stage winner LeMond. He now led his teammate by only forty seconds in the general classification.<ref name=tenstages/>\n\nThe race then moved over to the Alps. On stage 17, Hinault got left behind on the [[Col d'Izoard]] and lost the yellow jersey to LeMond, falling to third in the overall rankings, 2:47 minutes behind his teammate.{{sfn|Moore|2011|pages=240\u2013241}} Stage 18 featured three major climbs, the [[Col du Galibier]], the [[Croix de Fer]] and the final ascent up to Alpe d'Huez. Hinault attacked repeatedly, but reached the bottom of Alpe d'Huez with LeMond. He led the way up the climb, lined by approximately 300,000 spectators and crossed the finish line hand in hand with LeMond, in an apparent display of comradery. [[Urs Zimmermann]], who had been second overall at the start of the day, lost more than five minutes.<ref name=alpedhuez/> Any signs of appeasement between the rivalling teammates was shattered by Hinault in a television interview shortly after the stage finish, when he declared that the race was not yet over, even though he trailed LeMond by 2:45 minutes.{{sfn|Moore|2011|pages=255\u2013258}}\n\nStage 20 saw the final time trial and the last chance for Hinault to overcome LeMond's advantage. Aided by a crash from LeMond, Hinault won the stage, but gained back only 25 seconds, conceding defeat after the stage.{{sfn|Moore|2011|pages=266\u2013268}} He lost an additional 52 seconds on stage 21. In his last Tour de France stage into Paris, he took part in the final sprint, taking fourth place.{{sfn|Moore|2011|pages=271\u2013272}} He ended his final Tour de France second overall, 3:10 minutes behind LeMond. He won the [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]] and was also given the [[Combativity award in the Tour de France|super-combativity award]].{{sfn|Augendre|2018|p=77}}<ref>{{cite web |title=All about year 1986 |url=https://www.letour.fr/en/history |website=LeTour.fr |publisher=Amaury Sport Organisation |accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref> Hinault's repeated attacks during the race and refusal to concede defeat irritated LeMond, who felt betrayed by Hinault's lack of loyalty.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=Richard |title=LeMond and Hinault Near Fisticuffs! LeMond: \"Hinault's gonna pay.\" |url=https://www.velopress.com/lemond-and-hinault-near-fisticuffs-lemond-hinaults-gonna-pay/ |website=VeloPress |publisher=[[Competitor Group]] |accessdate=13 November 2019|date=11 July 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Chester |first1=Elliot |title=LeMond vs. the Badger: New film recalls cycling's stormy friendship |url=https://www.si.com/edge/2014/08/01/lemond-and-badger-new-film-focuses-cyclings-stormy-friendship |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=13 November 2019 |date=1 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Tour, Hinault won the [[Coors Classic]] race in the United States, ahead of LeMond.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=267\u2013268}}<ref name=\"1986worlds\">{{cite web |last1=Malach |first1=Pat |title=Gallery: 1986 Colorado Springs Worlds revisited |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/gallery-1986-colorado-springs-worlds-revisited/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=4 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104201239/http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/gallery-1986-colorado-springs-worlds-revisited/ |archivedate=4 January 2019 |date=16 September 2015}}</ref> He rode the [[1986 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|World Championships Road Race]], held in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]]. He aimed to win, showing a lot of effort in his preparation. However, he finished the race in 59th place.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abt |first1=Samuel |authorlink=Samuel Abt |title=Professional Title to Italian Cyclist |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/07/sports/professional-title-to-italian-cyclist.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=4 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104200733/https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/07/sports/professional-title-to-italian-cyclist.html |archivedate=4 January 2019 |date=7 September 1986}}</ref>{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=293}} On 19 September, he won his last competitive race, a criterium in [[Angers]], France.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=293}} Hinault's retirement from professional cycling on 14 November 1986 was celebrated in Quessoy with a symbolic race of 3,600 riders, a concert and fireworks. A total of 15,000 people attended the event.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=292}}\n\n== Retirement ==\n[[File:Bernard-Hinault-TdF2004.jpg|thumb|upright|Hinault in his role as presenter at the [[Tour de France]], in [[2004 Tour de France|2004]]|alt=Photograph of Hinault in a rain jacket, looking to the left]]\nAfter his retirement from professional cycling, Hinault moved to his farm and bred dairy cows, assisted by his cousin Ren\u00e9, who had become an agricultural engineer.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=304}} Just two weeks after he ended his career, the Tour de France organisers, [[Amaury Sport Organisation]] (ASO), approached Hinault and invited him to join the race management team. He held several positions, including race regulator and route advisor. After [[Jean-Marie Leblanc]] took over the role as general director, Hinault was named the Tour's ambassador. Included in his duties was being present during podium ceremonies.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=305}} During the podium for stage{{nbsp}}3 of the [[2008 Tour de France]], a protester jumped on stage and disturbed proceedings. Hinault leapt forward and shoved him off.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guinness |first1=Rupert |title=Protester finds French resistance from Badger |url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/protester-finds-french-resistance-from-badger-20080709-gdslci.html |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate=10 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110164423/https://www.smh.com.au/sport/protester-finds-french-resistance-from-badger-20080709-gdslci.html |archivedate=10 January 2019 |date=9 July 2008}}</ref> He stepped down from the role after the [[2016 Tour de France]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hood |first1=Andrew |title=ASO's podium bouncer Hinault to retire |url=https://www.velonews.com/2016/03/news/hinault-to-retire-from-aso_397622 |publisher=Pocket Outdoor Media, LLC. |website=[[VeloNews]] |accessdate=10 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110165104/https://www.velonews.com/2016/03/news/hinault-to-retire-from-aso_397622 |archivedate=10 January 2019 |date=7 March 2016}}</ref> His role as ASO's brand ambassador was taken over by Stephen Roche, winner of the [[1987 Tour de France]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ezvan |first1=Jean-Julien |title=Stephen Roche, nouvel ambassadeur du Tour 30 ans apr\u00e8s son triomphe |url=http://sport24.lefigaro.fr/cyclisme/tour-de-france/actualites/stephen-roche-nouvel-ambassadeur-du-tour-30-ans-apres-son-triomphe-866715 |newspaper=[[Le Figaro]] |accessdate=10 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110165451/http://sport24.lefigaro.fr/cyclisme/tour-de-france/actualites/stephen-roche-nouvel-ambassadeur-du-tour-30-ans-apres-son-triomphe-866715 |archivedate=10 January 2019 |language=French |date=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHinault never became a ''directeur sportif'', leading a team, after his active career, as did many of his competitors. Offers from [[Total Direct \u00c9nergie (cycling team)|Bouygues T\u00e9l\u00e9com]] and a Chinese investor in the mid-2000s fell through. He was the selector of the French national team from 1988 to 1993.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=306}} Hinault took a role as \"patron\" with the British {{ct|Vitus|2014}} squad for the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://roadcyclinguk.com/racing/tour-de-france-legend-bernard-hinault-becomes-team-raleigh-patron.html |title=Tour de France legend Bernard Hinault becomes Team Raleigh patron |last1=Henrys |first1=Colin |date=6 December 2013 |website=Road Cycling UK |accessdate=11 December 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110164810/https://roadcyclinguk.com/racing/tour-de-france-legend-bernard-hinault-becomes-team-raleigh-patron.html|archivedate=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Public image and riding style ==\n===Riding style and legacy===\nDuring his active career, Hinault was known as the ''patron'' of the field, meaning the rider with the highest authority. His biographer [[William Fotheringham]] has described him as \"the last of the sport's ''patrons''\".{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=11}} In this role, Hinault would use his influence with race organisers, control the pace of the peloton, and allow or refuse other riders the chance to attack. The riders' strike at Valence d'Agen in the 1978 Tour is cited as the first instance in which Hinault assumed this role.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=11\u201312}} His fellow riders stated that he, even though he did not talk much, was able to exert a high amount of certainty and therefore strength, which brought him respect and sometimes fear from his competitors.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=159}} To signal his authority, Hinault often symbolically rode at the front of the field, instead of in the slipstream of his teammates.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=205\u2013206}} His riding style has been described as \"fighting, full of aggression\", and he stated that when he did not feel good in a race, his reaction would be to attack.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|p=111}} Hinault described his own role as follows:\n{{quote|You are like a soldier, a general who dominates, who imposes his will on the others. I believe that you are born like that. Some are born to be workers, others to be in charge. I could have been a warlord. I would have waged war to win castles and land if I'd been born in the Middle Ages.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=203}}}}\n{{quote box|quote=\"Now, let's love him.\"<br /> Headline of the sports newspaper ''[[L'Equipe]]'' on the day after Hinault lost the [[1984 Tour de France]] to [[Laurent Fignon]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=239}}|width=20%|align=right}}\nHinault was however not always successful in his endeavours. During the 1980 Tour de France, he sought to remove the rule which excluded riders outside the time limit on each stage. He urged the riders to protest and ride slowly, but some did not follow his example, forcing Hinault to chase them down before he eventually left the race.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Der Zorn des Bretonen |journal=[[Der Spiegel]] |date=21 July 1980 |issue=30/1980 |pages=127\u2013128 |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-14315965.html |accessdate=10 January 2019 |trans-title=The Breton's Fury |language=German}}</ref> His enigmatic exit from the 1980 Tour created tensions with the press that would persist during the rest of his active career. By 1982, debates about his personality started to appear more and more in the media. Particular interest was given to an alleged lack of ''panache'' during his Tour wins and his behaviour towards fans and officials, whom he treated with open disgust.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=166\u2013167 & 176\u2013177}} Fotheringham suggests that Hinault only regained popularity with the French public after his knee problems and his Tour defeat in 1984.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=18}} Fellow racer Robert Millar suggested that in 1986 in particular, Hinault attempted to win over the French public by riding aggressively.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=289\u2013290}}\n\nHinault was not known to particularly enjoy going on training rides, unless he was specifically preparing for an event. He would often greet his training partners in a night gown when they arrived on time for training or have an easy day of training that included stops at a bakery for cake. His distaste for training became even more evident in the winter, when he would gain a lot of weight. Laurent Fignon described the first training camps of the year as follows: \"He looked as if he had been inflated. If you didn't know the Badger you would wonder how long it would take for him to get back to what he had been. You would be making a huge mistake.\"{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=169}} Hinault was capable of suffering through the training camp and returning to winning form within a month.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=168\u2013170}} Unlike a rider like Eddy Merckx, Hinault would not aim to win every race he entered. Millar described his approach as such: \"Hinault either cared or he didn't. When he didn't care about winning he'd bumble round and hurt you now and again just to remind you he was there.\"{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=17\u201318}}\n\nWith a r\u00e9sum\u00e9 of victories that includes all three Grand Tours (all of them more than once), the World Road Championships and a number of classics, Hinault has often been cited among the greatest cyclists of all time.<ref name=\"cn_greatest\"/><ref name=\"greatest\">{{cite magazine |title=Who is the greatest Grand Tour rider ever? |url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/who-is-the-greatest-grand-tour-rider-ever-175929 |magazine=[[Cycling Weekly]] |accessdate=14 November 2018 |date=14 October 2014}}</ref> The ''Historical Dictionary of Cycling'' describes him as \"one of the best riders ever\".<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Heijmans |editor1-first=Jeroen |editor2-last=Mallon |editor2-first=Bill |title=Historical Dictionary of Cycling |date=2011 |publisher=The Scarecrow Press |location=Plymouth |isbn=978-0-8108-7175-5 |pages=102\u2013103}}</ref> Comparisons are often drawn with Eddy Merckx, against whom Hinault rode at the beginning of his career. Lucien Van Impe commented: \"Merckx was the greatest, but Bernard [Hinault] was the most impressive.\"{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=17}} A study conducted in 2006, ranking Tour de France riders from 1953 to 2004 by different performance indicators, put Hinault as the top Tour rider of that period, ahead of Merckx and [[Lance Armstrong]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cherchye |first1=Laurens |last2=Vermeulen |first2=Frederic |title=Robust Rankings of Multidimensional Performances |journal=[[Journal of Sports Economics]] |date=2006 |volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=359\u2013373 |doi=10.1177/2F1527002505275092|url=https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/1527002505275092?ck=nck|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Nickname ===\nHinault was nicknamed ''le [[wikt:blaireau#French|blaireau]]'' in French, a term that can be translated into English as either \"the shaving brush\" or \"the badger\". According to Fotheringham, the nickname originates from Hinault's early training partners, [[Maurice Le Guilloux]] and [[Georges Talbourdet]], who would use the term to tease the young rider. Le Guilloux used it once in front of Pierre Chany, a writer for ''[[L'\u00c9quipe]]'', and the name stuck.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|pages=154\u2013155}}{{sfn|Moore|2011|p=21}} According to Hinault himself, the term in the first place was supposed to mean no more than \"mate\" or \"buddy\".{{sfn|Van Gucht|2015|p=14}} However, Hinault later embraced the association with the wild animal. In 2003, he commented: \"A badger is a beautiful thing. When it's hunted it goes into its sett and waits. When it comes out again, it attacks. That's the reason for my nickname. When I'm annoyed I go home, you don't see me for a month. When I come out again, I win.\"{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=156}} Hinault, as early as 1983, owned a stuffed badger to demonstrate his association with the animal.<ref name=tourdeforce/>\n\n=== Stance on doping ===\nHinault never tested positive for [[performance-enhancing drugs]] during his professional career and was never implicated in any doping practices.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dopingf\u00e4lle bei der Frankreich-Rundfahrt \u2013 Die Tour-T\u00e4ter |trans-title=Doping cases at the Tour de France - The Tour perpetrators|url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/sport/dopingfaelle-bei-der-tour-de-france-die-tour-taeter-1.117049-13 |newspaper=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |accessdate=10 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110224345/https://www.sueddeutsche.de/sport/dopingfaelle-bei-der-tour-de-france-die-tour-taeter-1.117049-13 |archivedate=10 January 2019 |language=German |date=6 February 2012}}</ref> He did, however, lead a riders' protest during a criterium race in [[Callac]] in 1982 against the sudden introduction of doping controls. He was handed a one-month suspended ban and fined [[Swiss franc|CHF]] 1,110, though the penalty was never enforced.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2015|p=205}}\n\nHinault has been outspoken about several prominent doping cases in the past years. In 2013, he heavily criticised [[Senate (France)|French senators]] for revealing the results of tests conducted in 2004 on samples from the [[1998 Tour de France]]. He called the initiative \"bullshit\" and urged lawmakers \"to stop bringing out the dead\", claiming they \"want to kill the Tour\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Hinault fears for Tour de France in light of doping drama |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/hinault-fears-for-tour-de-france-in-light-of-doping-drama/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111105143/http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/hinault-fears-for-tour-de-france-in-light-of-doping-drama/ |archivedate=11 January 2019 |date=27 June 2013}}</ref> In the same year, he reacted to comments made by Lance Armstrong, a rider stripped of seven Tour victories due to doping offences. Armstrong suggested that it would be impossible to win the Tour de France without performance-enhancing substances. To counter this claim, Hinault replied: \"He must not know what it was like to ride without doping.\" Armstrong later clarified that he had spoken about the time when he was riding (1999\u20132005).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pretot |first1=Julien |title=Winning without doping was impossible: Armstrong |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cycling-doping-armstrong-idUSBRE95R0QZ20130628 |accessdate=11 January 2019 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=28 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111110438/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cycling-doping-armstrong-idUSBRE95R0QZ20130628 |archivedate=11 January 2019 |location=Porto Vecchio}}</ref> In early 2018, Hinault also spoke out about the adverse analytical result for [[salbutamol]] of four-time Tour winner [[Chris Froome]] at the [[2017 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]. He criticised Froome for taking part in the [[2018 Giro d'Italia]] while the investigation was still ongoing. In addition, he commented that Froome could not be \"listed among the cycling greats\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kelner |first1=Martha |title=Chris Froome should not be listed with cycling greats, says Hinault |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/may/29/chris-froome-cycling-bernard-hinault-giro-ditalia |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111110911/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/may/29/chris-froome-cycling-bernard-hinault-giro-ditalia |archivedate=11 January 2019 |date=30 May 2018}}</ref> Froome would win the Giro and become the first rider since Hinault to hold all three [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tour]] Jerseys at once. Before the [[2018 Tour de France]], with Froome's case still ongoing, he urged the other riders to strike in protest if Froome competed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hinault calls for rider strike in protest of Froome at Tour |url=https://www.velonews.com/2018/06/road/hinault-calls-rider-strike-protest-froome-tour_470087 |website=[[VeloNews]] |publisher=Pocket Outdoor Media, LLC. |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111111152/https://www.velonews.com/2018/06/road/hinault-calls-rider-strike-protest-froome-tour_470087 |archivedate=11 January 2019 |date=20 June 2018}}</ref> Froome was later cleared of the charges and started the Tour where he finished third behind teammate [[Geraint Thomas]] and [[Tom Dumoulin]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=de Menezes |first1=Jack |title=Chris Froome cleared of failed drugs test and can compete in Tour de France 2018 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cycling/chris-froome-cleared-drugs-test-tour-de-france-2018-failed-why-can-he-compete-salbutamol-a8426361.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111111507/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cycling/chris-froome-cleared-drugs-test-tour-de-france-2018-failed-why-can-he-compete-salbutamol-a8426361.html |archivedate=11 January 2019 |date=2 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career achievements==\n===Major results===\n\nSource:<ref name=\"memoire\">{{cite web|title=Palmar\u00e8s de Bernard Hinault (Fra)|language=French|trans-title=Awards of Bernard Hinault (Fra)|url=http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.eu/palmares/hinault_bernard.php|work=Memoire du cyclisme|accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bernard Hinault|url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=8635|work=Cycling Archives|publisher=de Wielersite|accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"the-sports\">{{cite web|title=Bernard Hinault (France)|url=http://www.the-sports.org/bernard-hinault-cycling-spf46407.html|work=The-Sports.org|publisher=Info M\u00e9dia Conseil|accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;1972\n: 1st [[File:MaillotFra.PNG|20px]] [[French National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Junior Road Championships\n;1975\n: 1st [[File:MaillotFra.PNG|20px]] Individual pursuit, [[French National Track Championships|National Track Championships]]\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Circuit de la Sarthe (cycling)|Circuit de la Sarthe]]\n;1976\n: 1st [[File:MaillotFra.PNG|20px]] Individual pursuit, [[French National Track Championships|National Track Championships]]\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Circuit de la Sarthe (cycling)|Circuit de la Sarthe]]\n::1st Stage 3a\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Tour du Limousin]]\n::1st Stage 1\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall Tour de l'Aude\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall Tour d'Indre\u2013et\u2013Loire\n: 1st [[Paris\u2013Camembert]]\n;1977\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow-bluebar.svg|20px]] Overall [[1977 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]]\n::1st Stages 1 & 5\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Tour du Limousin]]\n::1st Stage 1\n: 1st [[1977 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]]\n: 1st [[1977 Gent\u2013Wevelgem|Gent\u2013Wevelgem]]\n: 1st [[Grand Prix des Nations]]\n;1978\n: 1st [[File:MaillotFra.PNG|20px]] [[French National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Road Championships\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[1978 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st Stages 8 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]), 15 & 20 (ITT)\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[1978 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n::1st Prologue, Stages 11b, 12, 14 & 18\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Crit\u00e9rium International]]\n::1st Stage 3\n: 1st [[Grand Prix des Nations]]\n: 2nd Overall [[1978 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]]\n: 3rd [[1978 Giro di Lombardia|Giro di Lombardia]]\n;1979\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[1979 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey green.svg|20px]] [[Points classification in the Tour de France|Points classification]]\n::1st Stages 2 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]), 3, 11 (ITT), 15 (ITT), 21 (ITT), 23 & 24\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow-bluebar.svg|20px]] Overall [[1979 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]]\n: 1st Overall [[Super Prestige Pernod International]]\n: 1st [[1979 Giro di Lombardia|Giro di Lombardia]]\n: 1st [[1979 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne|La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]]\n: 1st [[Grand Prix des Nations]]\n: 1st Stage 3 [[Tour de Luxembourg]]\n: 2nd Overall [[Crit\u00e9rium International]]\n: 2nd [[1979 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]]\n: 2nd [[French National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Road Championships\n: 8th [[1979 Gent\u2013Wevelgem|Gent\u2013Wevelgem]]\n;1980\n: 1st [[File:Jersey rainbow.svg|20px]] [[1980 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|Road race]], [[1980 UCI Road World Championships|UCI Road World Championships]]\n: 1st [[File:Jersey pink.svg|20px]] Overall [[1980 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]\n::1st Stage 14\n: [[1980 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st Prologue, Stages 4 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) & 5\n::Held [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] after Prologue, Stage 1a & Stages 11\u201312\n: 1st [[File:Jersey green.svg|20px]] Overall [[1980 Tour de Romandie|Tour de Romandie]]\n: 1st Overall [[Super Prestige Pernod International]]\n: 1st [[1980 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]]\n: 2nd [[French National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Road Championships\n: 3rd [[1980 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne|La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]]\n: 4th [[1980 Paris\u2013Roubaix|Paris\u2013Roubaix]]\n: 5th [[1980 Amstel Gold Race|Amstel Gold Race]]\n;1981\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[1981 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st [[Combination classification in the Tour de France|Combination classification]]<!-- no technicolour jersey before 1985 -->\n::1st Stages 7 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]), 16, 20 & 22 (ITT)\n::Overall [[Combativity award in the Tour de France|Combativity award]]<!-- no number bibs before 1998 -->\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow-bluebar.svg|20px]] Overall [[1981 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]]\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Crit\u00e9rium International]]\n: 1st Overall [[Super Prestige Pernod International]]\n: 1st [[1981 Paris\u2013Roubaix|Paris\u2013Roubaix]]\n: 1st [[1981 Amstel Gold Race|Amstel Gold Race]]\n: 3rd [[File:Bronze medal blank.svg|15px]] [[1981 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|Road race]], [[1981 UCI Road World Championships|UCI Road W