egory:Albums produced by Jimmy Iovine]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Greg Ladanyi]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Thom Panunzio]]\n[[Category:Arista Records albums]]\n{{1980s-rock-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Muso805", "label": "safe", "comment": "four star rating from 10 volume 4th Edition Oxford University Press, EPM 2007", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/See_the_Light_(The_Jeff_Healey_Band_album)"}
{"title_page": "Waamwang language", "text_new": "{{short description|Austronesian language spoken in New Caledonia}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Waamwang\n|nativename=\n|states=[[Voh, New Caledonia]]\n|extinct=?\n|ref=\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] \n|fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]]\n|fam4=[[Southern Oceanic languages|Southern Oceanic]]\n|fam5=New Caledonian \u2013 Loyalties \n|fam6=[[New Caledonian languages|New Caledonian]]\n|fam7=[[Northern New Caledonian languages|Northern New Caledonian]]\n|fam8=North Northern\n|fam9=Hmwaveke\n|iso3=wmn\n|glotto=waam1236\n|glottorefname=Waamwang\n}}\n'''Waamwang''' (Wamoang) is an extinct [[Kanak languages|Kanak language]] of [[New Caledonia]], in the commune of [[Voh]].<ref>{{Ethnologue16|wmn|Waamwang}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Southern Oceanic languages}}\n{{Languages of New Caledonia}}\n\n[[Category:Languages of New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of Oceania]]\n[[Category:New Caledonian languages]]\n\n\n{{SOceanic-lang-stub}}\n{{NewCaledonia-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Austronesian language sopken in New Caledonia}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Waamwang\n|nativename=\n|states=[[Voh, New Caledonia]]\n|extinct=?\n|ref=\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] \n|fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]]\n|fam4=[[Southern Oceanic languages|Southern Oceanic]]\n|fam5=New Caledonian \u2013 Loyalties \n|fam6=[[New Caledonian languages|New Caledonian]]\n|fam7=[[Northern New Caledonian languages|Northern New Caledonian]]\n|fam8=North Northern\n|fam9=Hmwaveke\n|iso3=wmn\n|glotto=waam1236\n|glottorefname=Waamwang\n}}\n'''Waamwang''' (Wamoang) is an extinct [[Kanak languages|Kanak language]] of [[New Caledonia]], in the commune of [[Voh]].<ref>{{Ethnologue16|wmn|Waamwang}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Southern Oceanic languages}}\n{{Languages of New Caledonia}}\n\n[[Category:Languages of New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of Oceania]]\n[[Category:New Caledonian languages]]\n\n\n{{SOceanic-lang-stub}}\n{{NewCaledonia-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Austronesier", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waamwang_language"}
{"title_page": "Aotearoa (Stan Walker song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Aotearoa\n| cover      = Aotearoa_Stan_Walker.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Stan Walker]] featuring [[Ria Hall]], Troy Kingi and Maisey Rika\n| album      =\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|07|21|df=yes}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=37}}\n| label      = [[Sony Music Australia|Sony]]\n| writer     = {{flat list|\n*Stan Walker\n*[[Ria Hall]]\n*Troy Kingi\n*Maisey Rika\n}}\n| producer   =\n| chronology = [[Stan Walker]]\n| prev_title = [[Holding You]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = Start Again\n| next_year  = 2015\n}}\n\n\"'''Aotearoa'''\" is a song by New Zealand recording artist [[Stan Walker]] featuring [[Ria Hall]], Troy Kingi and Maisey Rika. It was released as a [[single (music)|single]] through [[Sony Music Australia]] on 21 July 2014. \"Aotearoa\" peaked at number two on the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|New Zealand Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"Digital\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/aotearoa-maori-language-week/id896505259|title=iTunes Aotearoa (Maori Language Week 2014) [feat. Ria Hall, Troy Kingi & Maisey Rika] - Single |publisher=iTunes Store (New Zealand). Apple|accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nAn English version of the song was recorded and released on Walker's 2019 EP, ''[[Faith Hope Love (EP)|Faith Hope Love]]''.\n\n==Background==\nTo celebrate [[M\u0101ori Language Week]], Walker decided to release his first song completely in [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]], alongside other Kiwi artists [[Ria Hall]], Troy Kingi and Maisey Rika.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.morefm.co.nz/Stan-Walker-Releases-New-Song-Aotearoa/tabid/96/articleID/12856/Default.aspx#sthash.WBIKpPa9.dpuf |title=Stan Walker Released new song Aotearoa |publisher=morefm.co.nz|date=25 July 2014 |accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref> Inspired by the 1984 song \"[[Poi E]]\" by the Patea M\u0101ori Club, (which as of 2014 is the only M\u0101ori language song to reach number one on the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|New Zealand Singles Chart]]), Walker, Hall, Kingi and Rika took on the challenge to get another Maori song to number one in New Zealand. Of this initiative Walker says, \"we all have to connect ourselves back to the mainland where we are all from. I have never been more proud to be M\u0101ori. It doesn't matter who you are or where you've come from, to live in New Zealand, you are us and we are you. We are one!\"<ref name=\"flava.co.nz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.flava.co.nz/music/nzonair/aotearoa-stan-walker-ria-hall-maisey-rika-troy-kingi |title=Aotearoa Stan Walker Ria Hall Maisy Rika Troy Kingi |publisher=flava.co.nz |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=4 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904095903/http://www.flava.co.nz/music/nzonair/aotearoa-stan-walker-ria-hall-maisey-rika-troy-kingi |archivedate=4 September 2014 }}</ref> Hall calls the result \"a song to celebrate our nation, our landscape, our uniqueness, our language and our people\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzonscreen.com/title/aotearoa-2014 |title=Aotearoa 2014 |publisher=nzonscreen.com|date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref> A portion of the proceeds from \"Aotearoa\" went towards the Raukatauri Music Therapy Centre.<ref name=\"flava.co.nz\"/>\n\n==Video==\nA video was filmed with the artists in various locations around New Zealand, including Taupo and Whangarei. The director was Alice Orr.\n\n== Live performances ==\nOn 21 July 2014, \"Aotearoa\" was performed live on ''Breakfast''.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/breakfast-news/watch-stan-walker-performs-aotearoa-video-6033284 |title=Watch Stan Walker Perform Aotearoa |publisher=tvnz.co.nz|date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref> On 23 July 2014, the song was performed live on [[The Edge (radio station)|The Edge]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.theedge.co.nz/Stan-Walker-performs-his-new-song-Aotearoa-live-at-The-Edge/tabid/106/articleID/32246/Default.aspx |title=Stan Walker performs his new song Aotearoa live|publisher=www.theedge.co.nz|date=23 July 2014 |accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n  \n==Track listing==\n*;Digital download<ref name=\"Digital\" />\n# \"Aotearoa\" \u2013 3:13\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Aotearoa\" entered the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|New Zealand Singles Chart]] at number two on 28 July 2014; the following week, it fell to number seven.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://charts.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Stan+Walker+feat%2E+Ria+Hall%2C+Troy+Kingi+%26+Maisey+Rika&titel=Aotearoa&cat=s\n |title=STAN WALKER FEAT. RIA HALL, TROY KINGI & MAISEY RIKA - AOTEAROA (SONG)  |publisher=charts.nz (Hung Medien) |accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2014)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak <br /> position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|New Zealand|2|artist=Stan Walker|song=Aotearoa}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2014)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Recorded_Music_NZ|New Zealand Artist Top 50 Singles]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/nzsingles  |title=END OF YEAR CHARTS 2014  |publisher=Recording Industry Association of New Zealand (RIANZ) |year=2014|accessdate=31 December 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|}\n\n==Certification==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Certification\n|-\n| [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand]]\n| Gold<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/nzsingles?chart= |title=Top 20 New Zealand Singles Chart |publisher=Recorded Music NZ |date=27 July 2015 |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"   \n! scope=\"col\"| Country   \n! scope=\"col\"| Date   \n! scope=\"col\"| Format    \n! scope=\"col\"| Label   \n|-   \n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand<ref name=\"Digital\"/>   \n| 21 July 2014  \n| Digital download   \n| [[Sony Music Australia]]   \n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Stan Walker}}\n\n[[Category:Stan Walker songs]]\n[[Category:2014 songs]]\n[[Category:2014 singles]]\n[[Category:Sony Music Australia singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Stan Walker]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|other songs|Aotearoa (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Aotearoa\n| cover      = Aotearoa_Stan_Walker.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Stan Walker]] featuring [[Ria Hall]], Troy Kingi and Maisey Rika\n| album      =\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|07|21|df=yes}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=37}}\n| label      = [[Sony Music Australia|Sony]]\n| writer     = {{flat list|\n*Stan Walker\n*[[Ria Hall]]\n*Troy Kingi\n*Maisey Rika\n}}\n| producer   =\n| chronology = [[Stan Walker]]\n| prev_title = [[Holding You]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = Start Again\n| next_year  = 2015\n}}\n\n\"'''Aotearoa'''\" is a song by New Zealand recording artist [[Stan Walker]] featuring [[Ria Hall]], Troy Kingi and Maisey Rika. It was released as a [[single (music)|single]] through [[Sony Music Australia]] on 21 July 2014. \"Aotearoa\" peaked at number two on the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|New Zealand Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"Digital\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/aotearoa-maori-language-week/id896505259|title=iTunes Aotearoa (Maori Language Week 2014) [feat. Ria Hall, Troy Kingi & Maisey Rika] - Single |publisher=iTunes Store (New Zealand). Apple|accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nAn English version of the song was recorded and released on Walker's 2019 EP, ''[[Faith Hope Love (EP)|Faith Hope Love]]''.\n\n==Background==\nTo celebrate [[M\u0101ori Language Week]], Walker decided to release his first song completely in [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]], alongside other Kiwi artists [[Ria Hall]], Troy Kingi and Maisey Rika.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.morefm.co.nz/Stan-Walker-Releases-New-Song-Aotearoa/tabid/96/articleID/12856/Default.aspx#sthash.WBIKpPa9.dpuf |title=Stan Walker Released new song Aotearoa |publisher=morefm.co.nz|date=25 July 2014 |accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref> Inspired by the 1984 song \"[[Poi E]]\" by the Patea M\u0101ori Club, (which as of 2014 is the only M\u0101ori language song to reach number one on the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|New Zealand Singles Chart]]), Walker, Hall, Kingi and Rika took on the challenge to get another Maori song to number one in New Zealand. Of this initiative Walker says, \"we all have to connect ourselves back to the mainland where we are all from. I have never been more proud to be M\u0101ori. It doesn't matter who you are or where you've come from, to live in New Zealand, you are us and we are you. We are one!\"<ref name=\"flava.co.nz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.flava.co.nz/music/nzonair/aotearoa-stan-walker-ria-hall-maisey-rika-troy-kingi |title=Aotearoa Stan Walker Ria Hall Maisy Rika Troy Kingi |publisher=flava.co.nz |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=4 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904095903/http://www.flava.co.nz/music/nzonair/aotearoa-stan-walker-ria-hall-maisey-rika-troy-kingi |archivedate=4 September 2014 }}</ref> Hall calls the result \"a song to celebrate our nation, our landscape, our uniqueness, our language and our people\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzonscreen.com/title/aotearoa-2014 |title=Aotearoa 2014 |publisher=nzonscreen.com|date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref> A portion of the proceeds from \"Aotearoa\" went towards the Raukatauri Music Therapy Centre.