      = 0\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 6107\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\"/>\n|population_total         = 6004\n|population_density_km2   = 588.4\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|elevation_footnotes      =\n|elevation_m              = 440\n|elevation_ft             = 1444\n|coordinates              = {{coord|43|0|20|N|96|3|32|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 51041\n|area_code                = [[Area code 712|712]] Exchange: 737\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 19-59475\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0459884\n|website                  = {{URL|http://orangecityiowa.com/|City of Orange City}}\n|footnotes                =\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n}}\n'''Orange City''' is a city in, and the [[County seat|county seat]] of, [[Sioux County, Iowa|Sioux County]], [[Iowa]], United States.<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web |url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=June 7, 2011 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150503072804/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=May 3, 2015 }}</ref>  The population was 6,004 in the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], an increase from 5,582 in [[2000 United States Census|2000]].<ref name=\"IADC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iowadatacenter.org/archive/2011/02/feb10|title= Data from the 2010 Census|publisher=State Data Center of Iowa|accessdate=April 2, 2011}}</ref> Named after [[William III of England|William of Orange]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Orange City launches new branding initiative|url=http://orangecityiowa.com/blog/orange-city-launches-new-branding-initiative/|publisher=Orange City Iowa|accessdate=September 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402155323/http://orangecityiowa.com/blog/orange-city-launches-new-branding-initiative/|archivedate=April 2, 2012}}</ref> the community maintains its Dutch settler traditions visibly, with Dutch storefront architecture and an annual [[Tulip Festival]].<ref>Laura MacFarquhar, \"Our Town,\" ''The New Yorker,'' November 13, 2017.</ref>\n\n==History and culture==\nOrange City was first called Holland and was later renamed in honor of [[Dutch people|Dutch]] [[House of Orange-Nassau|royalty]]. The city was founded in 1870 by settlers from [[Pella, Iowa]] looking for cheaper and better land.<ref>Van Klompenburg, Carol; Crum, Doroty (1996). ''Dutch Touches, Recipes and Traditions''. Penfield Press, Iowa. {{ISBN|1-57216-024-1}}.</ref>\n\nAs the county seat of Sioux County, the city is the location of the [[Sioux County Courthouse (Iowa)|Sioux County Courthouse]], which is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nOrange City is located at {{coord|43|0|20|N|96|3|32|W|type:city}} (43.005498, \u221296.058796).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 23, 2011|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|3.94|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, all land.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web |title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=May 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112090031/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=January 12, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 320\n|1890= 1246\n|1900= 1457\n|1910= 1374\n|1920= 1632\n|1930= 1727\n|1940= 1920\n|1950= 2166\n|1960= 2707\n|1970= 3572\n|1980= 4588\n|1990= 4940\n|2000= 5582\n|2010= 6004\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=6107\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web|title=U.S. Census website|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=May 11, 2012}}</ref> of 2010, there were 6,004 people, 1,905 households, and 1,405 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|1523.9|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 2,004 housing units at an average density of {{convert|508.6|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 93.2% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.6% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.3% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.4% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 3.4% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 1.0% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 7.0% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,905 households of which 33.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 67.0% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 4.7% had a female householder with no husband present, 2.0% had a male householder with no wife present, and 26.2% were non-families. 23.5% of all households were made up of individuals and 10.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.61 and the average family size was 3.08.\n\nThe median age in the city was 29.1 years. 23.1% of residents were under the age of 18; 22.2% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 19.3% were from 25 to 44; 20.7% were from 45 to 64; and 14.7% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 47.3% male and 52.7% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=January 31, 2008|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 5,582 people, 1,719 households, and 1,285 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,808.5 people per square mile (697.5/km\u00b2). There were 1,805 housing units at an average density of 584.8 per square mile (225.5/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 97.51% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.50% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.05% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.97% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.61% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.36% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.13% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,719 households out of which 35.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 69.8% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 4.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 25.2% were non-families. 23.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 10.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.58 and the average family size was 3.07.\n\nAge spread: 22.7% under the age of 18, 24.9% from 18 to 24, 20.2% from 25 to 44, 16.3% from 45 to 64, and 15.9% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 28 years. For every 100 females, there were 85.7 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 80.6 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $39,721, and the median income for a family was $49,076. Males had a median income of $33,965 versus $21,130 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $17,413. About 4.4% of families and 4.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 3.8% of those under age 18 and 10.7% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Economy==\nMajor companies headquartered in Orange City include Diamond Vogel Paints, [[Pizza Ranch]], and Revival Animal Health Systems.\n\nEmployers in Orange City are:<ref>{{cite web|title=Major Employers|url=http://orangecityiowa.com/business/major-employers/|work=Orange City Iowa|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n* Diamond Vogel Paints & Old Masters \u2013 >800 employees\n* Orange City Area Health System \u2013 500 employees\n* Staples Promotional Products \u2013 400 employees\n* [[Northwestern College (Iowa)|Northwestern College]] \u2013 300 employees\n* Revival Animal Health \u2013 70 employees between its Orange City and [[Mapleton, Iowa]] facilities.\n* CIVCO (Radiation Oncology division) \u2013 270 employees worldwide\n* EZ-Liner \u2013 50 employees\n* Silent Drive \u2013 40 employees\n* [[Pizza Ranch]] \u2013 30 office staff\n* AIM Aerospace \u2013 110 employees\n* Van Beek Natural Science \u2013 25 employees\n\n==Education==\n[[MOC-Floyd Valley Community School District]] is the local school district.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://educateiowa.gov/sites/files/ed/documents/FY20_MOC-FLOYD%20VALLEY.pdf|title=MOC-Floyd Valley|publisher=[[Iowa Department of Education]]|accessdate=2020-03-27}}</ref> The district formed on July 1, 1994 with the merger of the Maurice-Orange City and Floyd Valley districts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.educateiowa.gov/sites/files/ed/documents/District%20Reorganization%20History%20final.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124738/https://www.educateiowa.gov/sites/files/ed/documents/District%20Reorganization%20History%20final.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2019-02-09|title=REORGANIZATION & DISSOLUTION ACTIONS SINCE 1965-66|publisher=[[Iowa Department of Education]]|accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref> Public schools serving the community are Orange City Elementary School, MOC-Floyd Valley Middle School in [[Alton, Iowa|Alton]], and MOC-Floyd Valley High School in Orange City. The current Orange City Elementary building opened in the early 1920s.<ref name=Dockterbond2020>{{cite web|author=Dockter, Mason|url=https://siouxcityjournal.com/news/local/moc-floyd-valley-puts-m-elementary-school-bond-measure-before/article_1948f188-32ce-57a4-9e3e-5c1dc4cca9db.html|title=MOC-Floyd Valley puts $37M elementary school bond measure before voters |work=[[Sioux City Journal]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-03-28}}</ref> As per the 2020 bond it will be rebuilt.<ref name=Hayworthbret>{{cite web|author=Hayworth, Bret|url=https://siouxcityjournal.com/news/local/state-and-regional/moc-floyd-valley-voters-pass-m-bond-for-elementary-school/article_96b58a41-247e-5775-9f24-33933265fda9.html|title=MOC-Floyd Valley voters pass $37M bond for elementary school in Orange City |work=[[Sioux City Journal]]|date=2020-03-03|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nPrivate schools include Orange City Christian School, and [[Unity Christian High School (Orange City)|Unity Christian High School]] in the [[War Eagle Conference]].\n\nOrange City is home to [[Northwestern College (Iowa)|Northwestern College]], a Christian [[liberal arts]] college affiliated with the [[Reformed Church in America]]. As of August 2011, 1,243 students were enrolled \u2013 59% female and 41% male.<ref>{{cite web|title=Northwestern Iowa|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/northwestern-iowa-1883|work=US News and World Reports - Best Midwest Colleges|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt is also within thirty miles of [[Northwest Iowa Community College]] in [[Sheldon, Iowa|Sheldon]], which was started in 1966 as a pilot program sponsored by the [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]] in cooperation with the local high schools. It enrolls over 1,000 students per year (58% female, 42% male as of 2005).\n\n==Religion==\nOrange City is traditionally a Dutch Reformed community with several congregations from the [[Christian Reformed Church of North America]], [[United Reformed Churches in North America]], and [[Reformed Church in America]] denominations. There are also congregations from the [[Lutheran Church\u2013Missouri Synod]], [[Southern Baptist Convention]], [[Presbyterian Church in America]], [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]], [[Christian and Missionary Alliance]], and [[Evangelical Free Church of America]] denominations.  A [[Catholic]] church is located in [[Alton, Iowa]], 3 miles East of Orange City.<ref>{{cite web|title=Churches in Orange City|url=http://orangecityiowa.com/residents/churches/|work=Orange City Iowa|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==<!--consensus reached to standardize this heading per WP:WikiProject Cities/US Guideline -->\n\n<!-- NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE\nOnly people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here as Notable people. This establishes notability.\nThe biographical article should say how they are associated with THIS CITY examples = born, raised, residing etc.\nAn external reliable source of their association with THIS CITY should be cited in their Article and MUST be cited HERE.\nAll others will be deleted without further explanation.\nAlphabetical by last name please. Use a short one line description of Notability.\nIf the person you think is Notable and does not have a Wikipedia Article for themselves, create one.\nGuidelines for the Notability of a person can be found by entering WP:PEOPLE in the wiki search.\nGuidelines on what is needed and how to write the Article can be found  by entering WP:MOSBIO in the wiki search.\nEND OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * END OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *END OF NOTICE -->\n* [[Nick Collison]] (born 1980) Former [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]] for the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] (2003-2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/collini01.html|title= Nicholas John Collison|publisher= BASKETBALL-Reference|accessdate=May 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Jordan De Jong]] (born 1979) Former [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] pitcher for the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] (2007)\n* [[Terry L. Huitink]] (1951\u20132014), Judge of the [[Iowa Court of Appeals]]; was born in Orange City.<ref>[http://publications.iowa.gov/135/1/judicial/3-5.html Iowa Court of Appeals]</ref>\n* [[Tyler James (American musician)|Tyler James]] (born 1982) Singer/songwriter<ref>{{cite news|title=Geertsmas move from Washington|url=http://siouxcounty.newspaperarchive.com/PdfViewer.aspx?img=153655847&currentPage=0|accessdate=January 25, 2012|newspaper=Sioux Center News|date=August 31, 1988}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tyler James Bio|url=http://tylerjames.com/bio|work=TylerJames.com|accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[James Kennedy (historian)|James Kennedy]] (born 1963) American historian<ref>{{cite news|last=Hytrek|first=Nick|title=Dutch photographer captures Orange City's heritage in book|url=http://siouxcityjournal.com/entertainment/books-and-literature/dutch-photographer-captures-orange-city-s-heritage-in-book/article_233fc28d-2047-554b-ab85-294b97f43ec3.html|newspaper=Sioux City Journal|accessdate=April 30, 2014|date=May 8, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Dennis Muilenburg]] (born 1964), Former President and CEO of [[The Boeing Company]].\n* [[Tyler Mulder]] (born 1987) [[United States|American]] [[Track and field|track and field athlete]] for [[Oregon Track Club]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unipanthers.com/sports/c-track/recaps/031508aab.html|title=NATIONAL CHAMPION: Mulder Wins 800 Meters|date=March 15, 2008|publisher=CBS Interactive/UNIPanthers|accessdate= May 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* Dr. Samuel Noordhoff (1927\u20132018), surgeon and missionary in Taiwan from 1959 to 1999, founder of the Noordhoff Craniofacial Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nncf.org/about/who_we_are/About_Dr.%20Samuel_Noordhof|title=About Dr. Samuel Noordhoff|website=Noordhoff Craniofacial Foundation|language=en|access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Kenneth Veenstra]], Iowa state legislator and businessman, lived in Orange City.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/6551/kenneth-veenstra Votesmart.org.-Kenneth Veenstra]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|first=Doug|first2=Tim|last2=Schlak|first3=Greta|last3=Grond|first4=Sarah|last4=Kaltenbach|last=Anderson|title=Orange City: Images of America|date=2014|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=9781467111584|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FfwZAwAAQBAJ&dq=Orange+City&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}<!-- for current and future use if material is uploaded -->\n{{Portal|Iowa}}\n* [http://www.orangecityiowa.com/ Orange City]\n* [http://www.city-data.com/city/Orange-City-Iowa.html City-Data] Comprehensive Statistical Data and more about Orange City\n\n<br/><!--this break is to put visual space between the last information and the following template if needed-->\n{{Sioux County, Iowa}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Dutch-American culture in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Cities in Sioux County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Cities in Iowa]]\n[[Category:County seats in Iowa]]\n[[Category:1884 establishments in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Orange City, Iowa|*]]\n[[Category:University towns in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Orange City, Iowa\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 =\n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Sioux county ia courthouse.jpg\n|imagesize                =\n|image_caption            = Sioux County Courthouse in Orange City\n|image_flag               =\n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = Sioux_County_Iowa_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Orange_City_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Orange City, Iowa\n|image_map1               =\n|mapsize1                 =\n|map_caption1             =\n| pushpin_map = USA\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in the United States\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{USA}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Iowa}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Iowa|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Sioux County, Iowa|Sioux]]\n|government_footnotes     =\n|government_type          = Mayor-council\n|leader_title             = Mayor\n|leader_name              = Deb De Haan\n|leader_title1            =\n|leader_name1             =\n|established_title        = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date         = February 29, 1884<ref>{{cite web|title=Orange City, Iowa|url=http://www.city-data.com/city/Orange-City-Iowa.html|publisher=City-Data|accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name =\"Gazetteer files\"/>\n|area_magnitude           =\n|area_total_km2           = 10.20\n|area_land_km2            = 10.20\n|area_water_km2           = 0\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 3.94\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 3.94\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 6107\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\"/>\n|population_total         = 6004\n|population_density_km2   = 588.4\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|elevation_footnotes      =\n|elevation_m              = 440\n|elevation_ft             = 1444\n|coordinates              = {{coord|43|0|20|N|96|3|32|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 51041\n|area_code                = [[Area code 712|712]] Exchange: 737\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 19-59475\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0459884\n|website                  = {{URL|http://orangecityiowa.com/|City of Orange City}}\n|footnotes                =\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n}}\n'''Orange City''' is a city in, and the [[County seat|county seat]] of, [[Sioux County, Iowa|Sioux County]], [[Iowa]], United States.<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web |url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=June 7, 2011 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150503072804/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=May 3, 2015 }}</ref>  The population was 6,004 in the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], an increase from 5,582 in [[2000 United States Census|2000]].<ref name=\"IADC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iowadatacenter.org/archive/2011/02/feb10|title= Data from the 2010 Census|publisher=State Data Center of Iowa|accessdate=April 2, 2011}}</ref> Named after [[William III of England|William of Orange]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Orange City launches new branding initiative|url=http://orangecityiowa.com/blog/orange-city-launches-new-branding-initiative/|publisher=Orange City Iowa|accessdate=September 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402155323/http://orangecityiowa.com/blog/orange-city-launches-new-branding-initiative/|archivedate=April 2, 2012}}</ref> the community maintains its Dutch settler traditions visibly, with Dutch storefront architecture and an annual [[Tulip Festival]].<ref>Laura MacFarquhar, \"Our Town,\" ''The New Yorker,'' November 13, 2017.</ref>\n\n==History and culture==\nOrange City was first called Holland and was later renamed in honor of [[Dutch people|Dutch]] [[House of Orange-Nassau|royalty]]. The city was founded in 1870 by settlers from [[Pella, Iowa]] looking for cheaper and better land.<ref>Van Klompenburg, Carol; Crum, Doroty (1996). ''Dutch Touches, Recipes and Traditions''. Penfield Press, Iowa. {{ISBN|1-57216-024-1}}.</ref>\n\nAs the county seat of Sioux County, the city is the location of the [[Sioux County Courthouse (Iowa)|Sioux County Courthouse]], which is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nOrange City is located at {{coord|43|0|20|N|96|3|32|W|type:city}} (43.005498, \u221296.058796).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 23, 2011|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|3.94|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, all land.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web |title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=May 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112090031/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=January 12, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 320\n|1890= 1246\n|1900= 1457\n|1910= 1374\n|1920= 1632\n|1930= 1727\n|1940= 1920\n|1950= 2166\n|1960= 2707\n|1970= 3572\n|1980= 4588\n|1990= 4940\n|2000= 5582\n|2010= 6004\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=6107\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web|title=U.S. Census website|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=May 11, 2012}}</ref> of 2010, there were 6,004 people, 1,905 households, and 1,405 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|1523.9|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 2,004 housing units at an average density of {{convert|508.6|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 93.2% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.6% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.3% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.4% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 3.4% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 1.0% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 7.0% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,905 households of which 33.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 67.0% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 4.7% had a female householder with no husband present, 2.0% had a male householder with no wife present, and 26.2% were non-families. 23.5% of all households were made up of individuals and 10.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.61 and the average family size was 3.08.\n\nThe median age in the city was 29.1 years. 23.1% of residents were under the age of 18; 22.2% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 19.3% were from 25 to 44; 20.7% were from 45 to 64; and 14.7% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 47.3% male and 52.7% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=January 31, 2008|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 5,582 people, 1,719 households, and 1,285 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,808.5 people per square mile (697.5/km\u00b2). There were 1,805 housing units at an average density of 584.8 per square mile (225.5/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 97.51% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.50% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.05% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.97% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.61% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.36% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.13% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,719 households out of which 35.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 69.8% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 4.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 25.2% were non-families. 23.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 10.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.58 and the average family size was 3.07.\n\nAge spread: 22.7% under the age of 18, 24.9% from 18 to 24, 20.2% from 25 to 44, 16.3% from 45 to 64, and 15.9% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 28 years. For every 100 females, there were 85.7 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 80.6 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $39,721, and the median income for a family was $49,076. Males had a median income of $33,965 versus $21,130 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $17,413. About 4.4% of families and 4.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 3.8% of those under age 18 and 10.7% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Economy==\nMajor companies headquartered in Orange City include Diamond Vogel Paints, [[Pizza Ranch]], and Revival Animal Health Systems.\n\nEmployers in Orange City are:<ref>{{cite web|title=Major Employers|url=http://orangecityiowa.com/business/major-employers/|work=Orange City Iowa|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n* Diamond Vogel Paints & Old Masters \u2013 >800 employees\n* Orange City Area Health System \u2013 500 employees\n* Staples Promotional Products \u2013 400 employees\n* [[Northwestern College (Iowa)|Northwestern College]] \u2013 300 employees\n* Revival Animal Health \u2013 70 employees between its Orange City and [[Mapleton, Iowa]] facilities.\n* CIVCO (Radiation Oncology division) \u2013 270 employees worldwide\n* EZ-Liner \u2013 50 employees\n* Silent Drive \u2013 40 employees\n* [[Pizza Ranch]] \u2013 30 office staff\n* AIM Aerospace \u2013 110 employees\n* Van Beek Natural Science \u2013 25 employees\n\n==Education==\n[[MOC-Floyd Valley Community School District]] is the local school district.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://educateiowa.gov/sites/files/ed/documents/FY20_MOC-FLOYD%20VALLEY.pdf|title=MOC-Floyd Valley|publisher=[[Iowa Department of Education]]|accessdate=2020-03-27}}</ref> The district formed on July 1, 1994 with the merger of the Maurice-Orange City and Floyd Valley districts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.educateiowa.gov/sites/files/ed/documents/District%20Reorganization%20History%20final.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124738/https://www.educateiowa.gov/sites/files/ed/documents/District%20Reorganization%20History%20final.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2019-02-09|title=REORGANIZATION & DISSOLUTION ACTIONS SINCE 1965-66|publisher=[[Iowa Department of Education]]|accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref> Public schools serving the community are Orange City Elementary School, MOC-Floyd Valley Middle School in [[Alton, Iowa|Alton]], and MOC-Floyd Valley High School in Orange City. The current Orange City Elementary building opened in the early 1920s.<ref name=Dockterbond2020>{{cite web|author=Dockter, Mason|url=https://siouxcityjournal.com/news/local/moc-floyd-valley-puts-m-elementary-school-bond-measure-before/article_1948f188-32ce-57a4-9e3e-5c1dc4cca9db.html|title=MOC-Floyd Valley puts $37M elementary school bond measure before voters |work=[[Sioux City Journal]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-03-28}}</ref> As per the 2020 bond it will be rebuilt.<ref name=Hayworthbret>{{cite web|author=Hayworth, Bret|url=https://siouxcityjournal.com/news/local/state-and-regional/moc-floyd-valley-voters-pass-m-bond-for-elementary-school/article_96b58a41-247e-5775-9f24-33933265fda9.html|title=MOC-Floyd Valley voters pass $37M bond for elementary school in Orange City |work=[[Sioux City Journal]]|date=2020-03-03|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nPrivate schools include Orange City Christian School, and [[Unity Christian High School]] in the [[War Eagle Conference]].\n\nOrange City is home to [[Northwestern College (Iowa)|Northwestern College]], a Christian [[liberal arts]] college affiliated with the [[Reformed Church in America]]. As of August 2011, 1,243 students were enrolled \u2013 59% female and 41% male.<ref>{{cite web|title=Northwestern Iowa|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/northwestern-iowa-1883|work=US News and World Reports - Best Midwest Colleges|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt is also within thirty miles of [[Northwest Iowa Community College]] in [[Sheldon, Iowa|Sheldon]], which was started in 1966 as a pilot program sponsored by the [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]] in cooperation with the local high schools. It enrolls over 1,000 students per year (58% female, 42% male as of 2005).\n\n==Religion==\nOrange City is traditionally a Dutch Reformed community with several congregations from the [[Christian Reformed Church of North America]], [[United Reformed Churches in North America]], and [[Reformed Church in America]] denominations. There are also congregations from the [[Lutheran Church\u2013Missouri Synod]], [[Southern Baptist Convention]], [[Presbyterian Church in America]], [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]], [[Christian and Missionary Alliance]], and [[Evangelical Free Church of America]] denominations.  A [[Catholic]] church is located in [[Alton, Iowa]], 3 miles East of Orange City.<ref>{{cite web|title=Churches in Orange City|url=http://orangecityiowa.com/residents/churches/|work=Orange City Iowa|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==<!--consensus reached to standardize this heading per WP:WikiProject Cities/US Guideline -->\n\n<!-- NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE\nOnly people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here as Notable people. This establishes notability.\nThe biographical article should say how they are associated with THIS CITY examples = born, raised, residing etc.\nAn external reliable source of their association with THIS CITY should be cited in their Article and MUST be cited HERE.\nAll others will be deleted without further explanation.\nAlphabetical by last name please. Use a short one line description of Notability.\nIf the person you think is Notable and does not have a Wikipedia Article for themselves, create one.\nGuidelines for the Notability of a person can be found by entering WP:PEOPLE in the wiki search.\nGuidelines on what is needed and how to write the Article can be found  by entering WP:MOSBIO in the wiki search.\nEND OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * END OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *END OF NOTICE -->\n* [[Nick Collison]] (born 1980) Former [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]] for the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] (2003-2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/collini01.html|title= Nicholas John Collison|publisher= BASKETBALL-Reference|accessdate=May 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Jordan De Jong]] (born 1979) Former [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] pitcher for the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] (2007)\n* [[Terry L. Huitink]] (1951\u20132014), Judge of the [[Iowa Court of Appeals]]; was born in Orange City.<ref>[http://publications.iowa.gov/135/1/judicial/3-5.html Iowa Court of Appeals]</ref>\n* [[Tyler James (American musician)|Tyler James]] (born 1982) Singer/songwriter<ref>{{cite news|title=Geertsmas move from Washington|url=http://siouxcounty.newspaperarchive.com/PdfViewer.aspx?img=153655847&currentPage=0|accessdate=January 25, 2012|newspaper=Sioux Center News|date=August 31, 1988}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tyler James Bio|url=http://tylerjames.com/bio|work=TylerJames.com|accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[James Kennedy (historian)|James Kennedy]] (born 1963) American historian<ref>{{cite news|last=Hytrek|first=Nick|title=Dutch photographer captures Orange City's heritage in book|url=http://siouxcityjournal.com/entertainment/books-and-literature/dutch-photographer-captures-orange-city-s-heritage-in-book/article_233fc28d-2047-554b-ab85-294b97f43ec3.html|newspaper=Sioux City Journal|accessdate=April 30, 2014|date=May 8, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Dennis Muilenburg]] (born 1964), Former President and CEO of [[The Boeing Company]].\n* [[Tyler Mulder]] (born 1987) [[United States|American]] [[Track and field|track and field athlete]] for [[Oregon Track Club]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unipanthers.com/sports/c-track/recaps/031508aab.html|title=NATIONAL CHAMPION: Mulder Wins 800 Meters|date=March 15, 2008|publisher=CBS Interactive/UNIPanthers|accessdate= May 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* Dr. Samuel Noordhoff (1927\u20132018), surgeon and missionary in Taiwan from 1959 to 1999, founder of the Noordhoff Craniofacial Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nncf.org/about/who_we_are/About_Dr.%20Samuel_Noordhof|title=About Dr. Samuel Noordhoff|website=Noordhoff Craniofacial Foundation|language=en|access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Kenneth Veenstra]], Iowa state legislator and businessman, lived in Orange City.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/6551/kenneth-veenstra Votesmart.org.-Kenneth Veenstra]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|first=Doug|first2=Tim|last2=Schlak|first3=Greta|last3=Grond|first4=Sarah|last4=Kaltenbach|last=Anderson|title=Orange City: Images of America|date=2014|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=9781467111584|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FfwZAwAAQBAJ&dq=Orange+City&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}<!-- for current and future use if material is uploaded -->\n{{Portal|Iowa}}\n* [http://www.orangecityiowa.com/ Orange City]\n* [http://www.city-data.com/city/Orange-City-Iowa.html City-Data] Comprehensive Statistical Data and more about Orange City\n\n<br/><!--this break is to put visual space between the last information and the following template if needed-->\n{{Sioux County, Iowa}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Dutch-American culture in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Cities in Sioux County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Cities in Iowa]]\n[[Category:County seats in Iowa]]\n[[Category:1884 establishments in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Orange City, Iowa|*]]\n[[Category:University towns in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toUnity Christian High School(link changed toUnity Christian High School (Orange City)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orange_City,_Iowa"}
{"title_page": "Abdullah al-Hamid", "text_new": "{{short description|Saudi poet and activist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n<!-- This article is written using conventions appropriate to American English, when style choices are made; see [[WP:ENGVAR]].-->\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Abdullah al-Hamid\n| image       = ACPRA 5th Trial Session 2.JPG\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Abdullah al-Hamid\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|7|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Buraidah]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2020|04|24|1950|7|12|df=yes}}\n| death_place = Riyadh\n| nationality = \n| awards = [[Right Livelihood Award]]\n| other_names = Abu Bilal\n| known_for   = Saudi poet, former Arabic professor, human rights activist and a co-founder of the [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]]\n| occupation  = \n}}\n'''Abdullah Hamid Ali al-Hamid''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u062d\u0627\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0644\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0627\u0645\u062f}}) or '''Abu Bilal''' was a Saudi poet, former Arabic professor, human rights activist and a co-founder of the [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]] (ACPRA).<ref name=\"BBCNews_Saudi_campaigner\"/> He has been imprisoned several times for supporting the establishment of a constitutional monarchy in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\" />\n\nIn May 2005, Dr. Abdullah al-Hamid was sentenced to seven years in prison for \"showing dissent and disobeying the ruler\" after calling for reforms.  He was pardoned and released on 8 August 2005.\n\nIn 2008, al-Hamid served a four-month prison term for \"incitement to protest\" after supporting a demonstration of women who were protesting the detention of relatives.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-punishes-two-activists-voicing-opinion-2013-03-11|title=Saudi Arabia punishes two activists for voicing opinion|last=|first=|date=11 March 2013|website=Amnesty International|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20130312000459/https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-punishes-two-activists-voicing-opinion-2013-03-11|archive-date=12 March 2013|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> The demonstration took place in front of [[Buraidah]] prison, in central Saudi Arabia. Demonstrations in Saudi's eastern province by members of the Shiite minority group calling for the release of prisoners have at times turned deadly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2013/03/01/world/meast/saudi-arabia-protest/index.html|title=161 arrested in Saudi Arabia protest over detentions|first=Mohammed |last=Jamjoom|website=CNN|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> In 2018, he was awarded the [[Right Livelihood Award]], together with other jailed activists and [[Waleed Abulkhair]] for \"their visionary and courageous efforts, guided by universal human rights principles, to reform the totalitarian political system in Saudi Arabia.\"\n\n== 2012 Legal case ==\nOn 1&nbsp;September 2012 Abdullah al-Hamid appeared in the [[Specialized Criminal Court]] together with [[Mohammad Fahad al-Qahtani|Mohammad al-Qahtani]].<ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\" /> Both read their defense statements to the court.<ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\" /> The charges against al-Hamid include \"spreading chaos, destabilizing public order, attempting to impede development in the country and questioning the integrity of official clerics by accusing them of being tools for the royal family\".<ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\" /> If convicted, he could face up to five years in prison. Another ACPRA co-founder, [[Mohammed Saleh al-Bejadi|Mohammed al-Bajadi]], received a four-year jail sentence on similar charges in April.<ref name=\"BBCNews_Saudi_campaigner\"/><ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\" />\n\n=== End of trial ===\nOn 9 March 2013, al-Hamid was sentenced to serve 5 years in prison, as well as to serve 6 years of a previous prison term that had been pardoned by King Abdullah in 2006, according to [[Abdulaziz al-Shubaily.|Abdulaziz Al-Shubaily]], an ACRPA member who said he attended the criminal court session in Riyadh. Al-Shubaily reported that the courtroom was \"full of journalists, activists, as well as a heavy security presence.\" Mohammad al-Qahtani was sentenced to 10 years in the same case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2013/03/09/world/meast/saudi-arabia-activists-sentenced/index.html|title=Two Saudis in human rights group get 10 years in prison|first=Mohammed |last=Jamjoom|website=CNN|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> The court also ordered the ACRPA to be closed, their funds confiscated, and their social media shut down.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Arrest of al-Hamid's lawyers ===\n[[Matrouk al-Faleh]] was arrested 19 May 2008, at his office at King Saud University in Riyadh, where he is professor of political science, and released on 10 January 2009. Al-Faleh, who had been acting as attorney for al-Hamid and his brother, [[Issa al-Hamid]], spent seven months in prison, held without charges in solitary confinement. It is believed the arrest was related to a letter written by al-Faleh detailing prison conditions after visiting Issa and Abdullah al-Hamid at al-Buraida prison.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www7.nationalacademies.org/humanrights/Cases/CHR_052154.htm | title=Case Information: Matrouk al-Faleh | publisher=Committee on Human Rights of the NAS, NAE and IOM | accessdate=16 March 2015 }}</ref> Al-Faleh is a member of the Paris-based [[Arab Commission for Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.frontlinedefenders.org/node/1765 | title=Saudi Arabia: human rights defender, Dr Matrouk Al-Faleh released after 235 days in prison | date=15 January 2009 | publisher=Front Line Defenders | accessdate=16 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[Abdulaziz al-Hussan]], who defended Mohammad al-Qahtani and Abdullah al-Hamid, was detained and interrogated in the spring of 2013, shortly after posting to Twitter about his clients\u2019 detention conditions.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-human-rights-activists-face-court-crackdown-intensifies-2013-11-28 | title=Saudi Arabia: Human rights activists face court as crackdown intensifies | date=28 November 2013 | publisher=Amnesty International | accessdate=16 March 2015 }}</ref> Rather than face a travel ban, which are typically imposed on anyone arrested, Al-Hussan moved to Bloomington Indiana, as visiting scholar at Indiana University's Center for Constitutional Democracy.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://inside.iub.edu/features/stories/2013-08-30-iniub-story-saudi-scholar.shtml | title=The situations and suffering of these people are huge | first=Brittany | last=Terwilliger | date=30 August 2013 | work=Inside IU Bloomington | publisher=Indiana University Bloomington | accessdate=16 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== International reaction ==\nOn 7&nbsp;September 2012, [[Amnesty International]] called for charges against al-Hamid and Mohammad al-Qahtani to be dropped, saying  the case appeared to be \"based solely on their legitimate work to defend human rights in Saudi Arabia and their criticism of the authorities.\" The organization called for a letter-writing campaign to the offices of the Saudi king and the minister of interior.<ref>[http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/09/07/236608.html \"Amnesty calls for case against Saudi human rights activists to be dropped\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6AVVmfxYo?url=http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/09/07/236608.html |date=7 September 2012 }}, 7&nbsp;September 2012, ''Al Arabiya News''. Retrieved 7&nbsp;September 2012.</ref> In 2018, he was awarded the [[Right Livelihood Award]].<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/world/2018/09/24/3-saudi-human-rights-activists-awarded-alternative-nobel.html 3 Saudi human rights activists awarded \"Alternative Nobel\"], JAN M. OLSEN, [[Fox News]], 24 September 2018</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nIn 9 April 2020, al-Hamid was [[Coma|comatose]] and transferred to critical care after suffering a [[stroke]], for which [[Amnesty International]] demanded his release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2020/04/saudi-arabia-prisoner-of-conscience-in-coma-still-detained-during-covid19-pandemic/|title=Prisoner of conscience in coma in Saudi Arabia still detained during COVID-19|last=|first=|date=17 April 2020|website=www.amnesty.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> Shortly after, while still under detention in 24 April 2020, he died at the age of 69.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arabi21.com/story/1263724/\u0648\u0641\u0627\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u062a\u0642\u0644-\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a-\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0627\u0645\u062f-\u0634\u064a\u062e-\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d\u064a\u064a\u0646|title=\u0648\u0641\u0627\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u062a\u0642\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0627\u0645\u062f.. \"\u0634\u064a\u062e \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d\u064a\u064a\u0646\"|last=|first=|date=24 April 2020|website=Arabi21|language=ar|trans-title=Saudi detainee, master of reformists, Abdullah al-Hamid died|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Walid Fitaihi]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"BBCNews_Saudi_campaigner\">{{cite web|title=Saudi campaigner Mohammad al-Qahtani goes on trial; 1&nbsp;September 2012 |publisher=BBC World Service |date=1 September 2012 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-19448323 |accessdate=3 September 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6APYN5sM9?url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-19448323 |archivedate=3 September 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\">{{cite web |title=Two prominent Saudi human rights activists on trial in Riyadh; 03&nbsp;September 2012 |publisher=Al Arabiya News |date=3 September 2012 |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/09/03/235859.html |accessdate=3 September 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6APYE80cJ?url=http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/09/03/235859.html |archivedate=3 September 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamid, Abdullah al-}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabian human rights activists]]\n[[Category:People from Buraidah]]\n[[Category:Right Livelihood Award laureates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Saudi poet and activist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n<!-- This article is written using conventions appropriate to American English, when style choices are made; see [[WP:ENGVAR]].-->\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Abdullah al-Hamid\n| image       = ACPRA 5th Trial Session 2.JPG\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Abdullah al-Hamid\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|7|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Buraidah]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2020|04|24|1950|7|12|df=yes}}\n| death_place = Riyadh\n| nationality = \n| awards = [[Right Livelihood Award]]\n| other_names = Abu Bilal\n| known_for   = Saudi poet, former Arabic professor, human rights activist and a co-founder of the [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]]\n| occupation  = \n}}\n'''Abdullah Hamid Ali al-Hamid''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u062d\u0627\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0644\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0627\u0645\u062f}}) or '''Abu Bilal''' was a Saudi poet, former Arabic professor, human rights activist and a co-founder of the [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]] (ACPRA).<ref name=\"BBCNews_Saudi_campaigner\"/> He has been imprisoned several times for supporting the establishment of a constitutional monarchy in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\" />\n\nIn May 2005, Dr. Abdullah al-Hamid was sentenced to seven years in prison for \"showing dissent and disobeying the ruler\" after calling for reforms.  He was pardoned and released on 8 August 2005.\n\nIn 2008, al-Hamid served a four-month prison term for \"incitement to protest\" after supporting a demonstration of women who were protesting the detention of relatives.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-punishes-two-activists-voicing-opinion-2013-03-11|title=Saudi Arabia punishes two activists for voicing opinion|last=|first=|date=11 March 2013|website=Amnesty International|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20130312000459/https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-punishes-two-activists-voicing-opinion-2013-03-11|archive-date=12 March 2013|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> The demonstration took place in front of [[Buraidah]] prison, in central Saudi Arabia. Demonstrations in Saudi's eastern province by members of the Shiite minority group calling for the release of prisoners have at times turned deadly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2013/03/01/world/meast/saudi-arabia-protest/index.html|title=161 arrested in Saudi Arabia protest over detentions|first=Mohammed |last=Jamjoom|website=CNN|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> In 2018, he was awarded the [[Right Livelihood Award]], together with other jailed activists and [[Waleed Abulkhair]] for \"their visionary and courageous efforts, guided by universal human rights principles, to reform the totalitarian political system in Saudi Arabia.\"\n\n== 2012 Legal case ==\nOn 1&nbsp;September 2012 Abdullah al-Hamid appeared in the [[Specialized Criminal Court]] together with [[Mohammad Fahad al-Qahtani|Mohammad al-Qahtani]].<ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\" /> Both read their defense statements to the court.<ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\" /> The charges against al-Hamid include \"spreading chaos, destabilizing public order, attempting to impede development in the country and questioning the integrity of official clerics by accusing them of being tools for the royal family\".<ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\" /> If convicted, he could face up to five years in prison. Another ACPRA co-founder, [[Mohammed Saleh al-Bejadi|Mohammed al-Bajadi]], received a four-year jail sentence on similar charges in April.<ref name=\"BBCNews_Saudi_campaigner\"/><ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\" />\n\n=== End of trial ===\nOn 9 March 2013, al-Hamid was sentenced to serve 5 years in prison, as well as to serve 6 years of a previous prison term that had been pardoned by King Abdullah in 2006, according to [[Abdulaziz al-Shubaily.|Abdulaziz Al-Shubaily]], an ACRPA member who said he attended the criminal court session in Riyadh. Al-Shubaily reported that the courtroom was \"full of journalists, activists, as well as a heavy security presence.\" Mohammad al-Qahtani was sentenced to 10 years in the same case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2013/03/09/world/meast/saudi-arabia-activists-sentenced/index.html|title=Two Saudis in human rights group get 10 years in prison|first=Mohammed |last=Jamjoom|website=CNN|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> The court also ordered the ACRPA to be closed, their funds confiscated, and their social media shut down.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Arrest of al-Hamid's lawyers ===\n[[Matrouk al-Faleh]] was arrested 19 May 2008, at his office at King Saud University in Riyadh, where he is professor of political science, and released on 10 January 2009. Al-Faleh, who had been acting as attorney for al-Hamid and his brother, [[Issa al-Hamid]], spent seven months in prison, held without charges in solitary confinement. It is believed the arrest was related to a letter written by al-Faleh detailing prison conditions after visiting Issa and Abdullah al-Hamid at al-Buraida prison.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www7.nationalacademies.org/humanrights/Cases/CHR_052154.htm | title=Case Information: Matrouk al-Faleh | publisher=Committee on Human Rights of the NAS, NAE and IOM | accessdate=16 March 2015 }}</ref> Al-Faleh is a member of the Paris-based [[Arab Commission for Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.frontlinedefenders.org/node/1765 | title=Saudi Arabia: human rights defender, Dr Matrouk Al-Faleh released after 235 days in prison | date=15 January 2009 | publisher=Front Line Defenders | accessdate=16 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[Abdulaziz al-Hussan]], who defended Mohammad al-Qahtani and Abdullah al-Hamid, was detained and interrogated in the spring of 2013, shortly after posting to Twitter about his clients\u2019 detention conditions.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-human-rights-activists-face-court-crackdown-intensifies-2013-11-28 | title=Saudi Arabia: Human rights activists face court as crackdown intensifies | date=28 November 2013 | publisher=Amnesty International | accessdate=16 March 2015 }}</ref> Rather than face a travel ban, which are typically imposed on anyone arrested, Al-Hussan moved to Bloomington Indiana, as visiting scholar at Indiana University's Center for Constitutional Democracy.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://inside.iub.edu/features/stories/2013-08-30-iniub-story-saudi-scholar.shtml | title=The situations and suffering of these people are huge | first=Brittany | last=Terwilliger | date=30 August 2013 | work=Inside IU Bloomington | publisher=Indiana University Bloomington | accessdate=16 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== International reaction ==\nOn 7&nbsp;September 2012, [[Amnesty International]] called for charges against al-Hamid and Mohammad al-Qahtani to be dropped, saying  the case appeared to be \"based solely on their legitimate work to defend human rights in Saudi Arabia and their criticism of the authorities.\" The organization called for a letter-writing campaign to the offices of the Saudi king and the minister of interior.<ref>[http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/09/07/236608.html \"Amnesty calls for case against Saudi human rights activists to be dropped\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6AVVmfxYo?url=http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/09/07/236608.html |date=7 September 2012 }}, 7&nbsp;September 2012, ''Al Arabiya News''. Retrieved 7&nbsp;September 2012.</ref> In 2018, he was awarded the [[Right Livelihood Award]].<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/world/2018/09/24/3-saudi-human-rights-activists-awarded-alternative-nobel.html 3 Saudi human rights activists awarded \"Alternative Nobel\"], JAN M. OLSEN, [[Fox News]], 24 September 2018</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nIn 9 April 2020, al-Hamid was [[Coma|comatose]] and transferred to critical care after suffering a [[stroke]], for which [[Amnesty International]] demaned his release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2020/04/saudi-arabia-prisoner-of-conscience-in-coma-still-detained-during-covid19-pandemic/|title=Prisoner of conscience in coma in Saudi Arabia still detained during COVID-19|last=|first=|date=17 April 2020|website=www.amnesty.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> Shortly after, while still under detention in 24 April 2020, he died at the age of 69.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arabi21.com/story/1263724/\u0648\u0641\u0627\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u062a\u0642\u0644-\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a-\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0627\u0645\u062f-\u0634\u064a\u062e-\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d\u064a\u064a\u0646|title=\u0648\u0641\u0627\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u062a\u0642\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0627\u0645\u062f.. \"\u0634\u064a\u062e \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d\u064a\u064a\u0646\"|last=|first=|date=24 April 2020|website=Arabi21|language=ar|trans-title=Saudi detainee, master of reformists, Abdullah al-Hamid died|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Walid Fitaihi]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"BBCNews_Saudi_campaigner\">{{cite web|title=Saudi campaigner Mohammad al-Qahtani goes on trial; 1&nbsp;September 2012 |publisher=BBC World Service |date=1 September 2012 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-19448323 |accessdate=3 September 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6APYN5sM9?url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-19448323 |archivedate=3 September 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"al-arabiya two prominent activists\">{{cite web |title=Two prominent Saudi human rights activists on trial in Riyadh; 03&nbsp;September 2012 |publisher=Al Arabiya News |date=3 September 2012 |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/09/03/235859.html |accessdate=3 September 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6APYE80cJ?url=http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/09/03/235859.html |archivedate=3 September 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamid, Abdullah al-}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabian human rights activists]]\n[[Category:People from Buraidah]]\n[[Category:Right Livelihood Award laureates]]\n", "name_user": "Rcb1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdullah_al-Hamid"}
